<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Steps Up Attacks in Belgrade  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO air raids destroyed a second  
bridge over the Danube, Serbian television reported today. The 
bridge is the second highway bridge in Novi Sad destroyed this 
week. NATO missiles knocked out a key bridge in the city on 
Thursday, blocking traffic on the waterway. Today's attack leaves 
only a railroad bridge in the city of 500,000. NATO Air Commodore 
David Wilby said alliance forces were targeting communications and 
transport links in their escalating campaign to force Yugoslav 
President Slobodan Milosevic to capitulate and stop his offensive 
in Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Macedonia Overwhelmed by Refugees  
</P>
<P>
	BLACE, Macedonia (AP) -- Macedonia announced today it won't  
accept any more refugees unless they can go on to other European 
countries. With an estimated 65,000 Kosovo Albanians jammed at its 
border and more coming, lack of toilets and running water have 
overwhelmed efforts by relief agencies to help. NATO spokesman 
Jamie Shea said that as many as 300,000 more refugees were believed 
to be en route to Kosovo's borders. 

</P>
<P>
	La. Twister Kills 9, Injures 100  
</P>
<P>
	BENTON, La. (AP) -- A tornado tore through this northwestern  
Louisiana town today, flattening homes and trapping people inside 
when walls collapsed around them. At least nine were killed when 
the twister swept through trailer parks just north of Shreveport 
and destroyed at least 30 house trailers. ``We're still searching 
and have so much to go through, there's no way of telling what the 
end total will be,'' said Bossier Parish Coroner Dawn Young. 

</P>
<P>
	NYPD Shooting Sparks D.C. Rally  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- About 2,500 demonstrators marched in  
Washington today calling for President Clinton and Congress to help 
combat police brutality. The rally was intended to call for changes 
to abusive police practices nationwide, but it was spurred by the 
shooting death of unarmed immigrant Amadou Diallo by four New York 
City police officers. Demonstrators wore buttons, T-shirts, fliers 
and posters with Diallo's picture and chanted his name. 

</P>
<P>
	Lockerbie Suspects Get Passports  
</P>
<P>
	CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Libya has provided passports to two suspects  
in the 1988 Pan Am bombing, a sign their promised handover was 
under way, Arab diplomats said today. Lamen Khalifa Fhimah and 
Abdel Basset Ali al-Megrahi are to be tried under Scottish law in 
the Netherlands.Diplomatic sources said both men have received 
their passports, which were taken from them by the Libyan 
government following their 1991 indictment by a U.S court. The Dec. 
21, 1988, bombing of the Pan Am jet over Lockerbie, Scotland, 
killed 270 people. 

</P>
<P>
	Radiation Case Reportedly Settled  
</P>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Families of 90 cancer patients who allege  
their relatives were unknowingly subjected to military-sponsored 
radiation experiments have reached a proposed $5 million 
settlement, The Cincinnati Enquirer reported today. The lawsuit 
alleged terminally ill cancer patients who sought treatment at 
Cincinnati General Hospital between 1960 and 1971 were given 
full-body and partial-body doses of radiation. The suit named the 
hospital and the federal government among defendants. The 
government was included in the suit because the Defense Department 
paid $651,000 for the test results to learn about the effects of 
radiation exposure. 

</P>
<P>
	Pope Leads Easter Ceremony  
</P>
<P>
	VATICAN CITY (AP) -- Marking the most solemn ceremony of the  
Catholic calendar, Pope John Paul II led clerics in procession 
through a darkened St. Peter's Basilica today, a candle-lit vigil 
for the coming of Easter. Thousands of faithful lit their own 
candles as he passed, filling the boundless darkness with glints of 
light. John Paul, appearing steadier and stronger than in his 
grueling schedule of Christmas services, is to deliver the address 
and celebrate Easter Mass tomorrow morning in St. Peter's. 

</P>
<P>
	Daylight Savings Time Begins Again  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- That hour of evening sunshine for ball games  
and barbecues is back with the return of daylight-saving time. The 
official moment for setting the clock ahead was 2 a.m. Sunday. The 
exceptions -- where standard remains all year -- are Arizona, Hawaii, 
the part of Indiana in the Eastern time zone, Puerto Rico, the 
Virgin Islands and American Samoa. Standard time will return Oct. 
31. 

</P>
<P>
	Magic Beat Pistons, 92-77  
</P>
<P>
	AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Penny Hardaway scored 20 of his  
game-high 30 points in the second half to lead the Orlando Magic to 
a 92-77 victory against the Detroit Pistons tonight. For the second 
time this season, Chuck Daly's Magic stopped his former team's 
winning streak at six games. The win also gives Orlando a 3-0 sweep 
of the season series. Darrell Armstrong added 16 points and 10 
assists for Orlando. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by STEPHANIE GASKELL  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
