<HEADLINE> It's Time To Think Earnings Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Now that the Dow 10,000 party is over, investors  
are returning to a more sobering concern: Did companies earn enough 
in the first quarter to justify their stratospheric stock prices? 
</P>
<P>
	In the next few weeks, earnings reports will determine whether  
the Dow can stay near its all-time closing high of 10,006.78 
reached last Monday. Despite the earnings warnings already issued 
by some high-profile companies, many analysts believe the Dow can. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think that first-quarter earnings are more likely to boost  
the market than drag it down,'' writes Edward Keon at Prudential 
Securities. ``Most companies probably feel pretty comfortable that 
they will meet or beat forecasts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts expect first-quarter profits for S&AMP;P 500 companies to  
be up between 5 percent and 6 percent from the first quarter of 
1998 after a flat fourth quarter and a drop of 3 percent in the 
third quarter of last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Fewer companies have warned of disappointing earnings this  
quarter, compared with the fourth quarter. By this point three 
months ago, 10 of the 30 Dow industrials had issued downbeat 
forecasts; so far this quarter just Coca-Cola and IBM have 
announced their sales would not meet expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	Profits have improved mostly because the U.S. economy continues  
to grow at a ferocious pace. Last Wednesday, the Commerce 
Department confirmed that the nation's gross domestic product grew 
at a 6 percent annual rate in the fourth quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Personal income and spending both grew in February, and a Money  
Magazine/ABC News poll showed consumer confidence held up in the 
face of NATO military strikes in Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Another reason for optimism is that foreign economies are doing  
less badly, which should benefit U.S.-based global companies. And 
the dollar remains weaker than it was for most of 1998. While that 
can make imports more costly, it boosts the value of U.S. profits 
earned overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	Leading the list of first-quarter earnings winners will be  
technology companies, expected to rise 37 percent, said analyst 
Joseph Abbott of I/B/E/S Inc., a provider of corporate earnings 
information based in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were hurt first by the Asian crisis and now they're  
recovering first,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Earnings at big Internet companies like America Online and Yahoo  
will also be higher, Abbott said. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecommunications profits are expected to be up 25 percent as  
companies benefit from Internet business and deregulation of the 
long-distance industry, said Chuck Hill, an analyst at First Call 
Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Earnings at consumer durable goods manufacturers should rise  
about 15 percent from last year, Abbott said. Most of that gain 
will come from auto companies. 
</P>
<P>
	To be sure, there are obstacles.  
</P>
<P>
	While there are signs of recovery in Asia and at least a  
containment of problems in Latin America, neither region is back on 
its feet yet. ``It wouldn't take much to go into another downward 
spiral again,'' Abbott said. 
</P>
<P>
	The conflict in Yugoslavia could derail economies in Europe,  
such as Germany and Italy, which are important U.S. trading 
partners and already teetering on the edge of recession. 
</P>
<P>
	Finally, domestic interest rates are about half a percentage  
point higher than they were at the beginning of the year. They 
could go higher if commodity prices continue to rise, or if the 
U.S. economy continues so strong that the Federal Reserve decides 
to brake it by raising interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Blots on the first-quarter earnings picture include energy,  
expected to be down 49 percent, and basic materials companies, down 
28 percent. These companies are just now beginning to benefit from 
higher oil and commodity prices, Hill said. 
</P>
<P>
	This past week, the Dow finally made its first close above  
10,000, but the blue chips gave up ground and ended the week only 
10.27 higher at 9,832.51. On Thursday the Dow was up 46.35; there 
is no trading on Good Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index rose 7.35 Thursday to 1,293.72.  
It was up 10.92 on the week. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nasdaq composite index rose 31.97 to 2,493.37 Thursday,  
giving it a gain of 74.20 for the week. The Russell 2000, 
reflecting the performance of smaller companies, rose 1.11 to 
398.74 Thursday, for a weekly gain of 4.82. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Stock Exchange composite rose 1.40 Thursday to  
604.99, picking up 2.64 during the week. The American Stock 
Exchange composite gained 1.00 Thursday to 711.30, but fell 7.44 on 
the week. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wilshire Associates Equity Index -- which represents the  
combined market value of all NYSE, American and Nasdaq issues -- 
ended the week at $11.769 trillion, up $110.03 billion from the 
previous week. A year ago the index stood at $10.672 trillion. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
