<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: No Target Is Off-Limits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As NATO missiles struck downtown Belgrade, the  
Clinton administration declared today that ``no target is 
off-limits'' in the campaign to pressure Serb forces to end their 
campaign of repression in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton, in his weekly radio address, declared the  
Kosovo operation ``a difficult and dangerous one, but it's 
necessary and right, and we must stand with all our NATO allies to 
see it through.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Our nation cannot do everything. We can't stop all the  
violence. But there are times when looking away simply is not an 
option,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also said the U.S. military would pitch in with  
humanitarian relief for what NATO spokesman Jamie Shea today called 
a ``demographic earthquake'' in the Balkans -- with 290,000 refugees 
having left Kosovo in the past 10 days and as many as 300,000 more 
moving toward the border. 
</P>
<P>
	An Air Force C-17 cargo plane was flying out of Dover Air Force  
Base, Del., this afternoon with 50,000 pounds of packaged meals, 
known as humanitarian daily rations, to feed Kosovar refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	Dover spokesman Tech. Sgt. Don Perrien said the C-17 was headed  
for Ramstein, Germany, headquarters of U.S. Air Force operations in 
Europe. The supplies then will be flown to the Balkans, he said. 
Perrien said that in the next several days Dover will be shipping 
as much as 1.1 million pounds of rations. 
</P>
<P>
	An administration official said the attacks in Belgrade ``made  
it clear we are targeting high-value targets, especially those 
assets Mr. Milosevic holds most dear -- his regular army and special 
forces.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The message is that no target is off-limits that is involved  
in the repression of Kosovo, including downtown Belgrade,'' 
National Security Council spokesman David Leavy said. 
</P>
<P>
	``As we move forward in the days to come, we will continue to  
intensify the strikes to make clear to Mr. Milosevic our 
determination to significantly degrade his military capability,'' 
he said, referring to Yugoslavia's president, Slobodan Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	After sea-based cruise missiles set a complex of military  
offices in downtown Belgrade afire early today, Pentagon spokesman 
Kenneth Bacon declared they hit buildings Milosevic ``uses to 
control the forces responsible for ethnic cleansing in Kosovo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The buildings house the Yugoslav Interior Ministry and  
headquarters for the Serb police, which U.S. officials say is 
leading the terror campaign in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore, interviewed by radio reporters just  
before the new missile strikes, said, ``Milosevic has barely begun 
to incur the damage he will feel to his military and police and the 
security apparatus by which he keeps his dictatorship in power, if 
he continues this activity and if he does not allow these innocent 
families to return to their homes with security and autonomy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ethnic Albanians comprised about 90 percent of Kosovo's prewar  
population, and the White House accuses Yugoslavia of trying to 
``depopulate'' the province. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated one-third of Kosovo's 2 million people have been  
driven from their homes. Scores of thousands have been forcibly 
sent to the borders since NATO airstrikes began last week. 
</P>
<P>
	At a White House briefing Friday, Julia Taft, assistant  
secretary of state for refugees, population and migration, said at 
least 344,830 ethnic Albanians have fled the province since last 
year. An additional 345,000 have been driven from their homes but 
are still within Kosovo, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton saluted NATO's decision to have its forces in Macedonia  
provide support and manpower to independent relief agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to support them in every way we can,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The United States has directed $91 million in humanitarian aid  
to the region since last year. Clinton authorized another $50 
million in support this week. He told the Pentagon to airlift food, 
tents and other relief supplies to neighboring countries unable to 
cope with the tide of refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the aircraft carrier Theodore Roosevelt, a symbol of  
American military might, entered the western Mediterranean Sea 
today and was heading toward the Adriatic Sea off the Yugoslav 
coast. Defense officials said it was likely to be ordered to stay 
in the Adriatic to join the NATO battle. 
</P>
<P>
	The air war against Yugoslavia has yet to use carrier-based  
aircraft, although Navy ships have fired Tomahawk cruise missiles 
at Yugoslav targets. 
</P>
<P>
	Bacon, the Pentagon spokesman, said Friday that if ordered into  
action, the Roosevelt, with 5,500 sailors and 75 aircraft aboard -- 
including 46 strike planes -- ``would bring a large amount of 
firepower to continue with our systematic, day and night attacks 
designed to choke off the Serb military.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The White House signaled that the campaign is likely to continue  
beyond just a few weeks. But no enthusiasm was seen for introducing 
American ground forces to supplement air and sea power, even though 
the president did not explicitly rule that out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
