<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Iowa Assistant Fighting for Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IOWA CITY, Iowa (AP) -- All the way back to his youth, Bob  
Elliott's life has been consumed by football. 
</P>
<P>
	He watched his father coach, he played the game, he became a  
coach himself. Elliott seemed destined to become a head coach, 
possibly of his beloved Iowa Hawkeyes. 
</P>
<P>
	All that has changed.  
</P>
<P>
	Instead of rearranging depth charts or tinkering with defensive  
alignments, Elliott will be going into the hospital to battle a 
life-threatening blood disorder. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the former top assistant at Iowa will begin a  
week-long barrage of chemotherapy and radiation treatments to 
prepare his body for a bone marrow transplant. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I said I wasn't afraid, I'd be lying,'' said Elliott, who  
turns 46 on May 6. ``There's significant risk of dying in a bone 
marrow transplant. To say otherwise is not realistic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Elliott suffers from a blood disorder called polycythemia vera.  
His bone marrow is hyperactive, producing too many white blood 
cells, too many red cells, too many platelets. 
</P>
<P>
	Left unchecked, the blood disorder could turn into leukemia.  
It's also possible that, with too many platelets, blood clots could 
form and lead to a heart attack or stroke. 
</P>
<P>
	The blood disorder led doctors at University Hospitals to remove  
Elliott's spleen in 1991 because of clotting. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since 1991, I've been in that hospital at least once a week  
with those doctors,'' said Elliott, a defensive back at Iowa in the 
early 1970s and a coach at the school for 12 years before stepping 
down late last year. 
</P>
<P>
	At the very least, the disorder could lead to fibrosis in the  
bones, preventing the bone marrow from making blood cells. 
</P>
<P>
	That would mean blood transfusions every other day, Elliott  
said, although no one knows if that would be two years down the 
road or 15 years from now. 
</P>
<P>
	So Elliott decided have the bone marrow transplant and believe  
in the odds -- he says they're about 60-40, perhaps even 70-30 -- 
that he'll survive. 
</P>
<P>
	Elliott is determined to return to coaching.  
</P>
<P>
	``That's the goal, to be able to coach again,'' he said. ``I  
think I'm a good football coach. I think that's what I was put on 
this earth to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Because of his health, Elliott no longer was a viable candidate  
to take over when Hayden Fry retired in November. Before his health 
worsened, Elliott, the son of former Iowa athletic director Bump 
Elliott, had been at or near the top of the list of possible 
successors. 
</P>
<P>
	But the job went to Kirk Ferentz, another former Fry assistant  
who had spent the last six years as the offensive line coach with 
the Baltimore Ravens. 
</P>
<P>
	Elliott will undergo seven or eight days of chemotherapy and  
radiation before doctors introduce the new bone marrow. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, for the following two to three weeks, it will be a waiting  
game as doctors determine if Elliott's system accepts the new 
marrow and begins producing blood cells. 
</P>
<P>
	For a while, anyway, football won't be so important.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
