<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Florida Prepares For More Fires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PALM COAST, Fla. (AP) -- The pictures under glass on Bill and  
Lorie Majewski's coffee table record the story of their loss and 
recovery over the last 10 months. 
</P>
<P>
	They lost all their worldly possessions on one windy summer  
afternoon when 21 homes in their community were destroyed and 37 
others were damaged by a wildfire, one that turned out to one of 
the first of a series of devastating blazes around the state. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, the Majewskis are working to rebuild their lives while  
state officials are gearing up for another dangerous spring and 
summer, hoping thunderstorms will come in May and June to end a 
winter drought. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are preparing for an extended dry period, but hoping for  
some water,'' said Terence McElroy, a spokesman for state 
Agriculture Commissioner Bob Crawford. ``It has been an incredibly 
dry winter and we've had a significant number of wildfires.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Division of Forestry's Wildfire Season Forecast predicts  
more wildfires than usual through May. Drought indexes -- which 
range from 0 to 800, with 800 being ``desert level'' -- are about 
650 in southern Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	And since Feb. 28, more than 900 fires have charred 28,000  
acres. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, one fire blazed through a large area of brush about  
15 miles south-southwest of downtown Miami. The size was not 
immediately determined. ``Most of the area out there is not 
accessible by road and it's rough terrain,'' said Miami-Dade Fire 
Rescue Capt. John Spadaro. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, sparks from the wheels of a train ignited a smoky  
blaze which closed about 10 miles of Interstate 75 in rural 
Charlotte and Lee counties. No one was hurt, and no homes were 
damaged, but the smoke blocked hundreds of motorists for about 30 
minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire that destroyed the Majewskis' two-story home last June  
6 was started by hunters on the other side of four-lane Seminole 
Woods Parkway. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Majewski and her husband were out with their oldest  
daughter, while her mother stayed at home with the other three 
children. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were assured it was under control,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	By the time they learned the fire had jumped the highway and was  
racing through their neighborhood, there was only time to get the 
family out. 
</P>
<P>
	Everything was destroyed -- videos they had taken of the children  
as toddlers, photographs, honors the children had won at school, 
even Mrs. Majewski's wedding rings. 
</P>
<P>
	The family was able to move into a new home on Feb. 10.  
</P>
<P>
	On the coffee table are photographs they retrieved from  
relatives or took since the fire. There is a picture of two of 
their children standing in the driveway of the house before it 
burned. There are photos of its gray ruins. There are pictures of 
the new house under construction. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Majewski still feels like a stranger in the new house.  
</P>
<P>
	``Nothing here belongs to me. I feel hollow,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Last year, heavy rain caused flooding in northern and central  
Florida during the winter and spring, but then the rain stopped. 
</P>
<P>
	By the time thunderstorms returned in mid-July, fires had raged  
across 500,000 acres around Florida, destroying 126 homes and 
damaging 211 others. At the start of the July 4 weekend, the 42,000 
people living in Flagler County were told to evacuate. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, the state is doing more to prevent fires, McElroy  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	More controlled burns are being done to reduce the amount of  
fuel before big blazes start up. Fire breaks are being built around 
neighborhoods near forested areas. Firefighting equipment and 
supplies are being positioned around southern Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Arsonists who are blamed for a third of the fires this spring  
also are being targeted, McElroy said, with a task force set up to 
track down and prosecute them. 
</P>
<P>
	And there's a possibility of rain next week, said Scott  
Goodrick, a Division of Forestry meteorologist. 
</P>
</TEXT>
