<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Apocalyptic' Books Now Big Sellers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) -- The approach of the year 2000 may be a  
devil of a problem for computer programmers, but it's heavenly for 
the $3 billion Christian book market. 
</P>
<P>
	Stores specializing in Christian products have seen a big  
increase in sales of books about endtime prophecies and the Y2K 
computer bug as believers become more focused on what might happen 
when the calendar turns to Jan. 1, 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the books examine current world events in a biblical  
context and conclude the time is ripe for the return of Jesus 
Christ. Others offer dire, Bible-based predictions of what may 
occur if computers fail worldwide because of the highly publicized 
year 2000 glitch. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the books are novels; others are classified as  
nonfiction. All are selling like crazy. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a nationwide trend,'' said Chris Rogers, merchandising  
vice president of Lifeway Christian Resources, a Nashville, Tenn., 
company with 81 Baptist bookstores in 20 states. ``No doubt about 
it, it's going to build.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As a Christian, Liz Dyson loves reading about what the future  
may bring. As the owner of Lemstone Books in suburban Birmingham, 
she likes the surging sales of endtime books, which are second only 
to Bibles in volume at her mall store. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody knows what's going to happen, really, and you see so  
much happening that was prophesied,'' said Mrs. Dyson. ``You see 
weather patterns changing, and nation against nation. People are 
wondering how much longer it can go on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Linda Stone has noticed a tremendous increase in sales of  
endtime books in recent months at Faith Book Store where she works 
in Gardendale, Ala. 
</P>
<P>
	``As soon as we get them in, they're gone,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Book stores trace much of the interest in the endtime genre to  
fear over the computer problem known as Y2K. Books such as the 
popular ``Millennium Meltdown'' discuss what could happen if 
computers programmed to read years by two digits only, confuse the 
``00'' in 2000 with 1900. 
</P>
<P>
	Nancy Guthrie, a spokeswoman for the Christian Booksellers  
Association, said three of the top seven books on the group's 
nonfiction best seller list deal directly with Y2K. 
</P>
<P>
	Also driving up sales are the Christian novels known as the  
``Left Behind'' series. The books by Tim LaHaye and Jerry Jenkins, 
along with a related children's series and audio books, have sold 
3.2 million copies since 1995. The fifth book in the series, 
``Apollyon,'' debuted recently. 
</P>
<P>
	The books, written like action novels with plenty of references  
to Bible verses, describe what will happen in the years following 
an event known as ``The Rapture,'' when many Christians believe the 
faithful will be taken to heaven in an instant before chaos 
envelops the world. Some claim the Y2K bug may be a precursor of 
those tumultuous times. 
</P>
<P>
	As much as she enjoys perusing the endtime section of her  
Christian book store, Mrs. Dyson isn't staying up nights fretting 
over the future. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't worry about it,'' she said, ``because I know God's  
going to take care of me.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
