<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pope Leads Solemn Easter Vigil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VATICAN CITY (AP) -- Marking the most solemn ceremony of the  
Catholic calendar, Pope John Paul II led clerics in procession 
through a darkened St. Peter's Basilica on Saturday, a candle-lit 
vigil for the coming of Easter. 
</P>
<P>
	``Light of Christ,'' a deacon intoned, in Latin, and John Paul  
bore a single 4-foot-tall candle through the pitch-black basilica. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of faithful lit their own candles as he passed,  
filling the boundless darkness with glints of light. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike past years, John Paul's homily for the vigil leading up  
to Easter Sunday was strictly religious, making no mention of the 
war over Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The only hint of the Balkan bloodshed was symbolic, in the  
selection of faithful from many nations for baptism in the ceremony 
-- this year, including one from Albania, as well as Cape Verde, 
China, France, Morocco and Hungary. 
</P>
<P>
	Although he has made numerous appeals for negotiations to end  
the crisis in Kosovo, John Paul has been publicly silent on the 
conflict over Easter weekend, instead stressing divine love as the 
hope of the world. 
</P>
<P>
	On Good Friday, the pope scrapped a prepared text that referred  
to Kosovo and deplored the triumph of ``the culture of death.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Italy's ANSA news service suggested the pontiff might use his  
traditional ``Urbi et Orbi'' address -- literally, ``To the City and 
to the World'' -- to ask on Sunday for opening of a humanitarian aid 
corridor in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	John Paul, appearing steadier and stronger than in his grueling  
schedule of Christmas services, is to deliver the address and 
celebrate Easter Mass on Sunday morning in St. Peter's. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
