<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Twin Boys Held in Father's Killing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Eleven-year-old twin brothers were spending  
the weekend in separate juvenile detention centers after being 
charged with killing their father and wounding their mother and 
sister. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators said they were trying to learn what set off the  
twins. Authorities say quit their shooting rampage after emptying a 
.32 caliber pistol. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't know what the spark was,'' Vance County Sheriff  
Thomas Breedlove said. ``There had to be one, but we're still 
looking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	William Harvey Bawcum Jr., 46, was gunned down Thursday night  
while rushing up a flight of steps to a bedroom where his wife had 
been shot in their home in Kittrell, about 35 miles north of 
Raleigh. 
</P>
<P>
	Deborah Bawcum, 45, was in good condition Saturday at Duke  
University Medical Center in Durham, where she recovered from a 
bullet wound to the right arm. Robin Bawcum, 16, was in fair 
condition at the same hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	The twins, whose names were not released, were each charged  
Friday with murder and two counts of assault with a deadly weapon. 
</P>
<P>
	They are too young to be tried as adults. If found to be  
delinquent, they could be held until they turn 18. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheriff's investigators said they had no record of calls to  
intervene in domestic troubles at the Bawcum home. 
</P>
<P>
	Neighbors described what appeared to be a stable country family.  
</P>
<P>
	The principal at Zeb Vance Elementary, where the boys were in  
the fifth grade, said the brothers were close, but not inseparable. 
Their worst offense recently was not turning in their homework a 
couple of weeks ago, said principal David Hawks. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was nothing in the classroom or in school overall that  
indicated to us that this could happen,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The boys were assigned guardians to act as their advocates.  
</P>
<P>
	One of the guardians, Harvey Johnson, said he talked to the  
boys, but would say little about his conversations other than that 
the shooting wasn't planned. 
</P>
<P>
	``Physically they're fine,'' he said. ``Mentally . . . that will  
come out later.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
