<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 9 Illegal Immigrants Dead in Storm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALPINE, Calif. (AP) -- They set out from Mexico three or four  
days ago, hiking north into rugged, unfamiliar mountains, some 
dressed only for mild, spring weather. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, in the final stretch of their trek, disaster struck: A  
surprise snowstorm brought frigid temperatures, leaving at least 
nine dead, seven in the United States and two in Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	Searchers with dogs and helicopters rescued more than 130 others  
on both sides of the border Friday, including some who wore only 
jeans, T-shirts and tennis shoes. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials blamed immigrant smugglers who callously lead  
their ill-prepared clients into dangerous terrain and then abandon 
them when trouble strikes. 
</P>
<P>
	But others say Operation Gatekeeper, the U.S. effort to shut  
down illegal immigration in the urban and suburban part of San 
Diego County, shares a major part of the blame by forcing 
border-crossers into more remote areas. 
</P>
<P>
	``Operation Gatekeeper has maximized the risks,'' said Claudia  
Smith, a spokeswoman for the California Rural Legal Assistance 
Foundation, a migrants' rights group. 
</P>
<P>
	The rescued migrants, whose journey was halted about 40 miles  
east of San Diego, were hospitalized and treated for hypothermia or 
exposure. They were then taken into U.S. Border Patrol custody for 
eventual return to Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the survivors, two young sisters between the ages of 5 and  
7 were in good condition late Friday, and authorities re-united 
them with an uncle who was part of the group. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 140 illegal immigrants died last year crossing from  
Mexico into California's San Diego and Imperial counties, said Bill 
Strassberger of the Immigration and Naturalization Service. About 
20 died this year before Friday's incident. 
</P>
<P>
	Several inches of snow were already on the ground in the  
Cleveland National Forest when another storm brought flurries 
Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities first learned about the stranded travelers when a  
woman, freezing from the cold, sought aid from a rancher near 
Alpine late Thursday. She told him that her husband and friend were 
lost in the storm, Strassberger said. 
</P>
<P>
	The rancher called Border Patrol agents, who found the body of  
the friend and later the husband, he said. Investigators then found 
a group of seven immigrants, triggering a full-scale rescue 
operation. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. rescuers found more than 50 people by late Friday and were  
trying to locate others reported missing by the migrants. Mexican 
authorities found two people dead near Tecate and 80 people 
stranded, Strassberger said. 
</P>
<P>
	Border Patrol supervisor Roy Villareal said several of the  
survivors told authorities they had arranged for smugglers to take 
them across the border, but were abandoned them when the weather 
got bad. 
</P>
<P>
	``They get a ride to the border; a smuggler leads them through  
the mountains, where another smuggler picks them up and takes them 
to a safe house,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	A Mexican national typically pays a smuggler $1,000 to $3,500.  
</P>
<P>
	Since 1994, when the federal government tripled patrols along  
the San Diego border as part of Operation Gatekeeper, migration has 
moved to more dangerous routes in the mountains and desert east of 
the city. 
</P>
<P>
	San Diego agents arrest as many as 500 illegal immigrants a day,  
mainly in the mountains, Villareal said. The Border Patrol 
estimates that hundreds of thousands cross each year without 
getting caught. 
</P>
<P>
	The Border Patrol has asked Mexican officials to warn people  
against making the trip, especially in bad weather. An El Nino 
storm last April left three migrants dead and a surprise snow storm 
in February 1997 claimed seven lives, Strassberger said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
