<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Search Continues for Atheist Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- FBI agents began searching a Texas ranch in  
an apparent attempt to locate the bodies of missing atheist leader 
Madalyn Murray O'Hair and two relatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. O'Hair vanished from San Antonio in 1995 with her son,  
granddaughter and $500,000 in gold coins. Her 1963 Supreme Court 
case led to the ban on organized prayer in public schools. 
</P>
<P>
	Ranch owner Joanne Friend said Friday she was startled when FBI  
agents knocked on her door and announced they had a warrant to 
search for the three bodies. 
</P>
<P>
	``They said they were looking for bodies,'' she told the Fort  
Worth Star-Telegram. ``They said they suspected they were there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI confirmed that a search warrant was executed but refused  
to elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're acknowledging that a search warrant was executed, but  
we're not acknowledging why we're doing it or whether there was any 
digging or whether it's related to the O'Hair investigation,'' said 
agent Mike Appleby. 
</P>
<P>
	The ranch is located near the town of Camp Wood, about 100 miles  
west of San Antonio. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas Department of Public Safety spokesman Tom Vinger told the  
Star-Telegram: ``We are assisting the FBI, searching for evidence 
related to Madalyn Murray O'Hair at an undisclosed location.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, David R. Waters, 52, the former office manager for  
Mrs. O'Hair, and Gary P. Karr, 50, were arrested on weapons 
charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Waters has denied involvement in the O'Hairs' disappearance, and  
neither man has been charged in connection with the case. 
</P>
<P>
	The San Antonio Express-News reported last Saturday that  
evidence puts Karr and Waters in San Antonio about the same time in 
1995. 
</P>
<P>
	A lawyer for Waters told the Express-News that he has been told  
by a federal prosecutor that Waters has been implicated in Mrs. 
O'Hair's slaying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
