<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Stunt Man' Starting for Rockies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- The self-proclaimed stunt man is going to have a  
starring role. 
</P>
<P>
	Lenny Harris, who prefers the term ``stunt man'' over ``utility  
player,'' will start in right field Sunday night when the Colorado 
Rockies open the season against the San Diego Padres at Monterrey, 
Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	The opportunity stems from an injury to four-time Gold Glove  
winner and reigning NL batting champion Larry Walker, recovering 
from a strained rib muscle. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm happy, shocked,'' Harris said Saturday. ``It's been a long  
time. I can't even remember the last time I started on opening day. 
I started with the Dodgers in 1990 or '91 at third base.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although he has a history of injuries, Walker has been in  
Colorado's opening-day lineup for the past four seasons. He swung a 
bat underwater Saturday in his first activity since injuring the 
rib muscle Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm optimistic about tomorrow still,'' he said. ``Who knows? I  
might pull the ace out of the hole and walk up there 10 minutes 
before the game and tell them I want to play. Stupider things have 
happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Walker, 32, said he is frustrated by his expanding reputation as  
an injury magnet. He has played in more than 150 games just once in 
nine major league seasons -- a subject that came up while 
negotiating a $75 million, six-year contract extension last month. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just signed this big contract and there's a lot of  
nay-sayers out there, a lot of people disputing how he's injured 
all the time, and here I am again injured, so it really (ticks) me 
off,'' Walker said. ``I want to get out there and prove people 
wrong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Walker's slowly improving health has prevented the Rockies from  
placing him on the 15-day disabled list. The subject was a touchy 
one for manager Jim Leyland as he prepared to start the season 
without one of baseball's best all-around players. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to talk about the DL. We're going to use these  
three days and re-evaluate him Tuesday,'' Leyland said. ``I'm not 
going to start crossing bridges before I get there. We'll have plan 
B, C, D, E and F if we have to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though his credentials fall short of Walker's, Harris has played  
every position but catcher, and he showed Saturday that he is a 
capable alternative. He homered, singled and drove in two runs in 
Colorado's 10-6 victory over the Boston Red Sox. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to lose my name. It's the stunt man work that I  
do, so I'm just picking up the MVP player for us,'' Harris said. 
``Hopefully he can get back on target and get this team going.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
