<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican Fans Root for Castilla  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) -- Opening day will be more like Vinny  
Castilla day. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the trailblazing and defending NL champion San Diego  
Padres are the ``home'' team for Sunday night's game against the 
Colorado Rockies, Castilla can expect a hero's welcome when big 
league baseball returns to Mexico for what's being billed as the 
International Opener. 
</P>
<P>
	And the pressure will be on, because everyone in this  
baseball-mad industrial city wants to see the Rockies slugger hit 
home runs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Castilla has brought a lot of Mexicans into baseball,'' Carlos  
Chavez, 30, said Saturday while waiting in line for an attraction 
at the Baseball Festival at a park next to 26,000-seat Estadio 
Monterrey. ``He's the star here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Is he ever, especially with the kids.  
</P>
<P>
	Alan Antonio Gonzales, 9, said he's a Rockies fan ``because of  
Vinny Castilla. He hits a lot of home runs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Little Leaguer was asked how many he'd like to see Castilla  
hit. 
</P>
<P>
	His father prompted him, saying: ``Well, he goes up to bat four  
times.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``About four,'' Gonzales replied.  
</P>
<P>
	Arturo Garza Nava, 8, predicted ``about three or four'' homers  
for the third baseman. 
</P>
<P>
	When asked what he knows about Castilla, the youngster said:  
``That he is very home-running, that he is from here in Mexico and 
nothing else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Enough said.  
</P>
<P>
	In August 1996, Fernando Valenzuela provided Monterrey fans with  
a memorable evening when he started and won the first 
regular-season big league game in Mexico, a 15-10 Padres victory 
over the New York Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	Fans hung on Valenzuela's every move, crowding the bullpen rails  
to watch him warm up and chanting ``Toro, Toro, Toro'' -- his 
nickname, Bull, in Spanish -- over and over. 
</P>
<P>
	Now it's Castilla who's the national hero.  
</P>
<P>
	Born in the southern state of Oaxaca, he is the greatest power  
hitter Mexico has produced. He's coming off a career year that saw 
him hit 46 homers, pushing his career total to 170, and drive in 
144 runs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will be a big day for me, a huge day for me,'' Castilla  
said just before the Rockies broke camp in Arizona. ``To be a part 
of this game, I'm very excited especially because I'm going to play 
in my country. I just can't wait to get down there and do some 
damage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He ought to love the bandbox Estadio Monterrey, which plays  
shorter than its listed dimensions of 325 feet down the lines and 
400 feet to center field. In three games in 1996, the Padres hit 
eight homers and the Mets one. 
</P>
<P>
	Among them were two memorable shots by Ken Caminiti in the  
series finale that helped propel him toward unanimous selection as 
NL MVP. Weakened by the brutal heat and food poisoning, Caminiti 
required two liters of IV fluid before the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Castilla hit six homers in 12 games against San Diego last year,  
including one off Sunday's starter, Andy Ashby. 
</P>
<P>
	Castilla said there's a chance he'll be too pumped up Sunday  
night. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll just play the way I play. I know there will be a lot of  
people cheering for me,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Colorado manager Jim Leyland, who makes his Rockies debut, has  
stressed to his team that this one counts. But he also wants 
Castilla and Roberto Ramirez, a former Padres pitcher who's also 
from Mexico, to have a good time. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to take anything away from Vinny or Roberto,''  
Leyland said. ``This is kind of their day, and I think that's the 
way we should approach it. But I want to be sure Vinny is kind of 
zeroed in, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the game, the teams will fly to San Diego where they'll  
finish the series with games Tuesday afternoon and Wednesday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* Castilla said he'll wear No. 14 instead of his usual No. 9  
for the game in tribute to former teammate Andres Galarraga, who 
will miss this season while undergoing treatment back cancer. ``Cat 
says he feels good and says he will be back next year,'' Castilla 
said. ``He is upbeat, and I want to let him know we are thinking 
about him. This is my way to show him support.'' ... Tony Gwynn 
begins the season 72 hits shy of 3,000. ... In Ashby's last 
appearance that counted, he was shelled in Game 2 of the World 
Series at Yankee Stadium. ... Colorado will start Darryl Kile, who 
was 13-17 last year. ... The game was a quick sellout, and scalpers 
were asking the equivalent of $150 for box seat tickets that had a 
face value of about $30. ... The Rockies won't need to pack parkas. 
Their exhibition game against Boston on Friday in Denver was snowed 
out, but it's hot and humid in Monterrey. It was 86 degrees on 
Saturday, with a high of 75 forecast for Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
