<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 09:12:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Iverson, 76ers Coach Trade Barbs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Star guard Allen Iverson and Philadelphia  
76ers coach Larry Brown have had a rocky relationship since Brown's 
arrival nearly two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The tension flared again Friday night when Iverson sat out the  
final three quarters in an 85-80 loss to the Cleveland Cavaliers. 
</P>
<P>
	The team's official explanation: Iverson had a ``mild sprain''  
of his already severely bruised right quadriceps. But there was 
clearly more to it than that. 
</P>
<P>
	Iverson was benched for the opening 2 minutes, 3 seconds, of the  
second quarter after going 0-for-7 in the first quarter. When Brown 
told Iverson to go back into the game, Iverson muttered, ``It's 
about ... time you put me back in,'' or something like that, the 
Philadelphia Inquirer and Daily News reported Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown pulled him out again, and Iverson sat the rest of the  
game. Iverson didn't even participate in halftime warmups or sit on 
the bench until the third quarter was under way. 
</P>
<P>
	Iverson said he was not going to play at Toronto Sunday and was  
doubtful for Tuesday's home game against Milwaukee because of his 
thigh, injured March 19 against the Los Angeles Lakers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It hasn't gotten any better,'' he said. ``I've never had  
anything like this before. Ever. ... It feels the same as when I 
first did it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Without mentioning Iverson by name, Brown, at a postgame press  
conference, questioned whether his players were making winning 
their primary focus. 
</P>
<P>
	The dispute raised old questions about Iverson's compatibility  
with his coach. A year ago, Brown urged Iverson to become more of a 
playmaker instead of a shooter, publicly criticizing Iverson's 
running of the team, his defense and his off-the-court lifestyle. 
</P>
<P>
	Iverson responded by vowing he would ``remember everything come  
contract time'' -- although in January he signed a six-year, $70.9 
million contract extension. 
</P>
<P>
	Iverson sought to downplay Friday's quarrel.  
</P>
<P>
	``There ain't no problems,'' he said after the game.  
``Everything ain't going to be peaches and cream all the time. But 
I don't have any problems with him.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
