<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 15:12:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Serbs Fire at NATO Troops in Bosnia  
</P>
<P>
	SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) -- NATO-led troops came under  
fire today while destroying the Bosnian portion of a key rail link 
between Serbia and Montenegro. The commander of the NATO-led forces 
in Bosnia, U.S. Gen. Montgomery Meigs, said the stabilization 
force, known as SFOR, fired back and that his forces suffered no 
casualties. Bosnian Serb television claimed the SFOR soldiers 
killed a railway guard. The television showed what appeared to be a 
body lying in the grass and a witness saying SFOR soldiers attacked 
the guard and that he did not resist. The Bosnian Serb claim could 
not be independently confirmed. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Destroys Bridge in Yugoslavia  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO air strikes today destroyed a  
second bridge over the Danube at Novi Sad, local media reports 
said. Serbian television reported some cars may have been on the 
bridge hit today in Serbia's second-largest city. The independent 
Beta news agency said seven people were injured, some seriously. 
Another independent agency, FoNet, reported that the attack left 
Novi Sad without water. NATO said earlier today that its forces had 
demolished a highway bridge farther downstream, cutting a major 
road link between Belgrade and Hungary. 

</P>
<P>
	Macedonia May Stop Taking Refugees  
</P>
<P>
	BLACE, Macedonia (AP) -- Macedonia announced today it won't  
accept any more refugees unless they can go on to other European 
countries. With an estimated 65,000 Kosovo Albanians jammed at its 
border and more coming, lack of toilets and running water have 
overwhelmed efforts by relief agencies to help. NATO spokesman 
Jamie Shea said that as many as 300,000 more refugees were believed 
to be en route to Kosovo's borders. 

</P>
<P>
	Report: Gov't Settles Radiation Suit  
</P>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Families of 90 cancer patients who allege  
their relatives were unknowingly subjected to military-sponsored 
radiation experiments have reached a proposed $5 million 
settlement, The Cincinnati Enquirer reported today. The lawsuit, 
filed five years ago, alleged terminally ill cancer patients who 
sought treatment at Cincinnati General Hospital between 1960 and 
1971 were given full-body and partial-body doses of radiation so 
researchers could measure the effects. Terms of the settlement also 
include an apology from the government and a memorial plaque to be 
placed on the University of Cincinnati campus listing the patients' 
names. 

</P>
<P>
	'Melissa' Suspect To Plead Innocent  
</P>
<P>
	TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- The man accused of creating the so-called  
Melissa virus, which infected thousands of computers and overloaded 
e-mail systems worldwide, never intended to do anything wrong, his 
lawyer said today. David L. Smith, a 30-year-old computer 
programmer, will plead innocent to the state charges, lawyer Steven 
Altman said. Smith faces charges that include interruption of 
public communications, conspiracy and theft of computer service -- 
charges that carry a maximum penalty of 40 years in prison and a 
$480,000 fine. 

</P>
<P>
	Pope Leads Solemn Easter Vigil  
</P>
<P>
	VATICAN CITY (AP) -- Marking the most solemn ceremony of the  
Catholic calendar, Pope John Paul II led clerics in procession 
through a darkened St. Peter's Basilica today, a candle-lit vigil 
for the coming of Easter. Thousands of faithful lit their own 
candles as he passed, filling the boundless darkness with glints of 
light. Unlike past years, John Paul's homily for the vigil leading 
up to Easter Sunday was strictly religious, making no mention of 
the war over Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Russian Official Sees Surplus  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia could attain a 2.5 percent budget surplus  
by 2000 if the country's relations with the International Monetary 
Fund continue to improve, a news agency reported today. The 
government hopes the IMF will give it a steady supply of loans over 
the next several years to pay off old debts and revive its economy. 
But given that Russia's economy is in deep recession and faces 
chronically bad tax collection and massive debts, such a growth 
forecast seems unlikely to be reached. 

</P>
<P>
	Nets Beat Heat 88-77  
</P>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Kendall Gill tied an NBA record  
with 11 steals and the New Jersey Nets turned Miami's sudden slump 
even worse today, beating the Heat 88-77. Gill had a triple-double 
with 15 points and 10 rebounds, and his 11 steals tied the record 
set by Larry Kenon of San Antonio against Kansas City on Dec. 26, 
1976. 

</P>
<P>
	Cink, Weir Share BellSouth Lead  
</P>
<P>
	DULUTH, Ga. (AP) -- Stewart Cink and Mike Weir shared the lead  
after today's third round of the BellSouth Classic, with David 
Duval lurking near the top once again. Duval, who hoped to use this 
tournament as a relaxing warm-up for the Masters, will have to 
change his focus now that another victory is in sight, the product 
of a third straight sub-70 round. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by STEPHANIE GASKELL  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
