<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> San Fran Court Going to the Dogs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Does your neighbor's dog howl at the moon  
until 2 a.m.? Did the pit bull next door eat your hamster? Is 
little Fifi sneaking into your yard and leaving unwanted mementos? 
</P>
<P>
	Justice goes to the dogs in San Francisco, thanks to William  
Herndon, a police sergeant who also is a judge, presiding for the 
past five years over Dog Court. 
</P>
<P>
	Herndon loves dogs -- he has two, an Australian shepherd named  
Bart and a mixed breed he calls Lisa -- and wants to protect owners' 
rights to their animals, as long as the city's human population 
isn't in jeopardy. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a very important job. I take it real seriously,'' he  
said. ``I want to do right for the people, for the dogs and make it 
safe for the city.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Herndon's charter is a section of the city's health code. Owners  
can ask to have the case transferred to Superior Court, although it 
doesn't happen often. 
</P>
<P>
	The people on both sides of the issue show up, tell their  
stories, and present witnesses if necessary. Occasionally an 
attorney shows up, but generally these sessions are informal and 
casual. 
</P>
<P>
	Herndon can send both sides home to work out their difficulties  
or can have the dog euthanized (that happens about 20 percent of 
the time). In about half of the cases, he orders the dog leashed or 
muzzled in public, or sends it to a canine behavior expert -- a dog 
shrink. 
</P>
<P>
	Herndon, 45, heard three cases on a recent Thursday, the only  
day his court is in regular session. 
</P>
<P>
	The first two were fairly routine, both involving unleashed dogs  
biting other dogs. Herndon said he would make a ruling at a later 
date. 
</P>
<P>
	The third case was more serious, involving pit bulls Buggsy and  
Cookie who were owned by Sergio Guevara. Neighbor Curtis Norman 
alleges that when he tried to shoo the dogs out of his yard, Buggsy 
bit him on the arm. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Norman seems willing to forgive and forget if Guevara  
fixes the fence between their yards, Norman's wife, Arlene, isn't 
as accepting. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to be attacked,'' she said with a scowl,  
mentioning visiting grandchildren. 
</P>
<P>
	Herndon told Guevara to take his dogs to the Department of  
Animal Care and Control for examination by a behaviorist. 
</P>
<P>
	Buggsy bit the behaviorist. The injury wasn't severe, but that  
was it for Buggsy; a destruction order was issued. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've never had that happen before,'' Herndon said of the  
attack. 
</P>
<P>
	The fate of Cookie, who didn't join the attack, was still to be  
determined. 
</P>
<P>
	Some cases end up much as they might in some instances of  
disturbing human behavior. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had the case of a Jack Russell terrier who lived in a  
neighborhood where people left their doors open,'' Herndon said. 
``The dog got loose and ran into a neighbor's house, where he 
chased the people around.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nobody was bitten, but that still amounted to ``menacing  
behavior.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The dog wound up on Prozac because he was so high-strung,''  
Herndon said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990403.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 08:15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Daughter Admits To Killing Mom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- It was an October afternoon when Susan Marie  
Watson walked into a Newark police interview room. She was there to 
discuss her mother's murder 27 years earlier, and Detective Rashid 
Sabur knew exactly what she would say. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said, `She's gonna lie, she's gonna lie,''' recalled Sabur,  
one of two detectives comprising Newark's recently formed cold-case 
squad. ```But then she's gonna tell the truth.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Two hours later, tears streaming down her face, she did just  
that. In 1971, 14-year-old Susan Marie Watson had cold-bloodedly 
murdered her own mother. Her stunned husband asked why she had 
confessed this horrible secret to a pair of total strangers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I trusted them,'' replied the 41-year-old mother of three.  
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Watson's arrest is an example of cold-case success, a  
combination of archaeology and old evidence, of instinct and 
amateur psychology. It began -- as many such cases do -- with a phone 
call from a family member. 
</P>
<P>
	Her brothers, George and David Johnson, had read about the  
cold-case squad's formation last fall. They wanted Sabur and 
partner Keith Sheppard to reinvestigate their mother's murder. 
</P>
<P>
	The facts were fairly basic.  
</P>
<P>
	Maylon Johnson, while lying in bed, was shot to death in the  
early morning hours of Oct. 3, 1971. Her nightclothes bore a single 
bullet hole. The lone witness, her daughter Susan Marie, called 
police and implicated the dead woman's boyfriend. 
</P>
<P>
	He instantly became the main suspect, but the trail just as  
quickly grew cold. The murder of Maylon Johnson became another 
unsolved homicide, ignored for years -- until the cold-case squad 
phone rang this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	The Johnson brothers offered new information: they believed  
their mother was possibly dating a second man, someone apart from 
the suspect named by their sister. 
</P>
<P>
	Sabur and Sheppard reopened the case. They mounted a dig in the  
police property room, rooting through dirty boxes and decades of 
accumulated dust. They located the file and studied old evidence 
for something the original investigators may have missed. 
</P>
<P>
	The pair next hit the streets, reinterviewing everybody  
connected with the case. They tracked down Susan Marie Watson in 
Schenectady, N.Y., where she was married with three girls of her 
own and working as a keyboard operator. 
</P>
<P>
	She had a new life. But her old life was soon to intrude.  
</P>
<P>
	As he read Mrs. Watson's 1971 interview, Sabur sensed something  
wrong: ``She was doing a lot of dancing around.'' One specific 
thing bothered him: There was a two-hour gap between the time of 
death and the arrival of police. 
</P>
<P>
	``My thing is, being the suspicious person that I am, that this  
girl waited two hours to get her story together because she killed 
her mom,'' said the veteran homicide detective. ``She panicked. She 
sat there and said, `What lie can I tell so they won't focus in on 
me?''' 
</P>
<P>
	His instinct, combined with some new details from from her  
brothers, convinced Sabur there was no mysterious boyfriend: Maylon 
Johnson was killed by her daughter. 
</P>
<P>
	When he first saw Mrs. Watson, Sabur recalled, her body language  
sent the same message. But their conversation Oct. 23, 1998, didn't 
focus on her guilt. 
</P>
<P>
	The detectives instead chatted with Mrs. Watson over two hours,  
becoming the distressed woman's ``best friends,'' Sabur recalled. 
Slowly, she opened up. 
</P>
<P>
	She told the detectives that she was sexually abused by the  
mother's boyfriend. She said her mother had done nothing to stop 
it. And then, weeping before the two detectives, she confessed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Throughout my years as a police officer, I never felt what I  
felt in that room,'' Sheppard said later. ``The feelings were 
overwhelming when she confessed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Watson's brothers have declined comment.  
</P>
<P>
	The case resulted in an unusual legal situation: Mrs. Watson was  
charged as a juvenile, since she was 14 when the crime occurred. 
</P>
<P>
	Sentencing guidelines for juveniles have since changed. In 1971,  
she could have been held only until age 21. Now she could face 20 
years. The case has yet to go to trial; a plea bargain is possible. 
</P>
<P>
	Either way, Sabur has little sympathy.  
</P>
<P>
	``The Ten Commandments say, `Thou shall not kill,''' the  
detective says matter-of-factly. ``You understand what I'm saying? 
So now it's up to us to go and get these individuals responsible 
for these deaths and bring them to justice -- not only in the eyes 
of society, but in the eyes of God.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990403.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 14:41:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Swimmer's Streak Ended by Dutch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- After 12 races in three days, Jenny Thompson  
was worn down by the World Short-Course Swimming Championships' 
tough new schedule, which includes semifinals for the first time. 
</P>
<P>
	In race No. 12, Thompson's winning streak at the championships  
ended Saturday, broken by Inge de Bruijn of the Netherlands in the 
50-meter freestyle. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson will have a chance Sunday to add another gold medal to  
the two she already won. She also has a $15,000 bonus for a world 
record in another event she didn't win, because she dropped out 
after breaking the record in the heats. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson swam five races Saturday, and in the fifth de Bruijn  
rallied over the final 25 meters and beat her, 24.35 seconds to 
24.57. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt good about my swim,'' Thompson said. ``Inge deserved  
that. She's good in the 50.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In line with a new format being adopted for the Olympics, this  
meet has semifinals for races of 100 meters or less -- meaning all 
of Thompson's events. For races of 200 meters or more, the eight 
fastest from the heats go directly into the finals. 
</P>
<P>
	In semifinals in the 100-meter butterfly, less than an hour  
before her 50 freestyle final, Thompson was only fourth-fastest at 
59.08. 
</P>
<P>
	But Thompson, who holds the world record of 56.90, had 24 hours  
to rest before the final. 
</P>
<P>
	American Kurt Grote, the world long-course champion in the 200  
breaststroke, was fastest Friday in the semifinals for the 100 at 
59.77. But in Saturday's final, he finished eighth at 1:00.28, with 
Patrik Isaksson winning at 59.69. 
</P>
<P>
	Isaksson's gold was Sweden's third of the meet, but Sweden's  
women, world record-holders in the 800 freestyle relay, missed a 
sweep of the freestyle relays when they were disqualified for an 
early takeoff in the 400. 
</P>
<P>
	The Swedes were fastest at 3:36.05, but the gold went to Britain  
at 3:36.88. 
</P>
<P>
	That, plus a gold by world record-holder James Hickman in the  
men's 200 butterfly, gave Britain a total of three golds, the same 
as Japan. Australia leads with five golds. 
</P>
<P>
	World record-holder Sandra Voelker of Germany spoiled Japanese  
Mai Nakamura's attempt for a second gold medal, winning the 50 
backstroke. Voelker's time of 27.63 was slower than her world mark 
of 27.27. 
</P>
<P>
	In Thompson's absence, Slovakia's Martina Moravcova won the  
women's 100 individual medley at 1:00.20, nearly a second slower 
than Thompson's record of 59.30. 
</P>
<P>
	World record holder Jani Sievinen of Finland won the men's 100  
individual medley at 54.18 and Russia's Nadejda Chemezova took the 
women's 400 freestyle at 4:05.23. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990403.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 14:41:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
