<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                        *Gladys Hasty Carroll    	
</P>
<P>
	SOUTH BERWICK, Maine (AP) -- Gladys Hasty Carroll, a writer known  
for her portrayals of rural life in Maine in the early 20th 
century, died Sunday. She was 94. 
</P>
<P>
	Carroll's most famous work, the 1933 best-seller ``As the Earth  
Turns,'' was a Pulitzer Prize nominee that inspired a Hollywood 
production the following year. 
</P>
<P>
	Carroll wrote 21 other works of fiction and nonfiction,  
including short stories and children's books. 
</P>
<P>
	A native of Rochester, N.H., Carroll spent her childhood and  
much of her adult life in the farmhouse her grandfather built 
during the Civil War in Dunnybrook, a tiny hamlet in South Berwick. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Dr. Harold Greenwald    	
</P>
<P>
	SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) -- Dr. Harold Greenwald, a  
psychotherapist whose dissertation on the psychology of prostitutes 
was turned into a best-selling book and Hollywood movie, died 
Friday. He was 88. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenwald wrote ``The Call Girl: A Social and Analytic Study''  
in 1958, which was reissued as ``The Elegant Prostitute.'' It sold 
more than a million copies and was translated into seven languages. 
</P>
<P>
	The book was later used as the basis for the 1960 film, ``Girl  
of the Night,'' starring Anne Francis and Lloyd Nolan. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenwald was known among psychologists for his development of  
direct decision therapy, which held that decisions were the key to 
understanding personality and dysfunctional patterns. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Wilson Riles    	
</P>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO (AP) -- Wilson Riles, California's first black  
statewide elected official, died Thursday. He was 81. 
</P>
<P>
	Riles became state schools superintendent in 1970, serving as  
California's leading schools advocate. He had a 12-year tenure 
before losing election in 1982. 
</P>
<P>
	Riles went to work for the state Department of Education in  
1958, heading a program to encourage schools to hire minority 
teachers. 
</P>
<P>
	As superintendent, Riles supported school integration but  
opposed mandatory busing. He also advocated higher testing 
standards. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Jesse Stone    	
</P>
<P>
	ALTAMONTE SPRINGS, Fla. (AP) -- Jesse Stone, a major influence on  
20th century music who wrote ``Shake, Rattle and Roll'' and helped 
develop many of Atlantic Records' biggest hits, died Thursday. He 
was 97. 
</P>
<P>
	As a writer, producer and arranger at Atlantic, Stone worked  
with artists such as Ray Charles, Big Joe Turner, the Drifters and 
the Clovers. Among his other famous songs were ``Idaho'' and 
``Money Honey.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stone helped build Atlantic Records into a top rhythm-and-blues  
label in the late '40s and early '50s, signing such stars as Ruth 
Brown. In 1954, Bill Haley had a Top 10 hit with Stone's ``Shake, 
Rattle and Roll.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stone's jazz tune ``Idaho'' helped make Guy Lombardo famous,  
selling 3 million copies in the mid-1940s. 

</P>
<P>
                     *Joseph ``Mighty Joe'' Young    	
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Blues guitarist Joseph ``Mighty Joe'' Young, who  
brought a special passion to the blues and helped introduce the 
musical form to mainstream America, died March 24 of complications 
following spinal surgery. He was 71. 
</P>
<P>
	Young began playing in the early 1950s, working clubs in  
Milwaukee and then back in his native Louisiana before moving to 
Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	In Chicago, he learned from such artists as Jimmy Rogers and  
Otis Rush, and appeared on records with Albert King and Koko 
Taylor. 
</P>
<P>
	Young was one of the first artists to bring blues to young,  
primarily white audiences on Chicago's North Side. He was also a 
popular draw on the festival and university circuits. 
</P>
<P>
	He released his final album in 1997, ``Mighty Man.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990403.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 14:51:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First American Wins Flamingo Stakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HIALEAH, Fla. (AP) -- First American, who had not won since  
breaking his maiden last September, earned a trip to the Kentucky 
Derby after pulling away for a 3 1/4-length victory in today's 
$250,000 Flamingo Stakes at Hialeah. 
</P>
<P>
	Ridden by Jose Velez Jr., First American stole the spotlight  
from heavily favored Prime Directive when he took the lead turning 
for home and eased away to cover 1 1/8 miles in 1:48 4-5. 
</P>
<P>
	``Absolutely, we're going to the Derby,'' trainer Eduardo  
Caramori said after First American paid $8, $4.40 and $3.40. ``He 
earned it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forty One Carats finished second and returned $8.80 and $7 and  
Vision and Verse paid $6.20 to show. Both were making their first 
starts in stakes competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Prime Directive, who went off at 4-5, finished sixth in the  
eight-horse field, 18 lengths behind the winner. 
</P>
<P>
	First American has won just two of eight starts, but Saturday's  
$150,000 purse increased his career earnings to $222,777. The son 
of Quiet American had failed to finish in the money in his three 
previous stakes, although he was just 2 1/2 lengths behind Vicar in 
the Florida Derby three weeks ago as a 119-1 shot. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've always been high on this colt, but we needed to win  
today to get his earnings to where he'd qualify for the Derby,'' 
said Caramori, who said he'd ship First American to Churchill Downs 
on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Prime Directive ran third entering the turn, but suddenly  
dropped off the pace and ran himself out of the Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's so much better than that,'' trainer Pat Byrne said.  
``We'll check him out and try to find a reason he stopped so badly. 
There's no chance for the Derby now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	First American didn't sustain his run in the Florida Derby, but  
did not falter Saturday as he stalked early leaders Shut Out Time 
and Forty One Carats. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got the position I wanted, about four or five lengths off  
the lead,'' said Velez, who was riding First American for the 
second time. ``When I asked him, he really responded. ... He's at 
his best when he's got a horse to run at.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shut Out Time set the pace through the first turn and down the  
backstretch, with Forty One Carats a half-length behind at the 
half-mile pole. Prime Directive ran third at that point. 
</P>
<P>
	Forty One Carats took the lead on the far turn as Prime  
Directive started to fade, then First American made his move. He 
drove past Forty One Carats at the top of the stretch as Vision and 
Verse moved into third. 
</P>
<P>
	First American led by two lengths at the eighth pole and drew  
out as Velez drove him with a left-handed whip. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
