<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 08:15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dodgers Try To Buy a Pennant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Just wondering, John Smoltz. All those wins in the '90s, all  
those October near misses, what does it all mean for the Atlanta 
Braves and their fans? 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the legacy is that they're going to appreciate it 10  
times more when it's over,'' the former Cy Young winner said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't mean anything now. We're still trying to win.''  
</P>
<P>
	The Braves have reached the NL championship series seven  
straight times, yet have only one World Series title. 
</P>
<P>
	The upstart Florida Marlins ended the Braves' season in 1997,  
and the San Diego Padres stopped them in 1998. So, is this the year 
someone else -- the Los Angeles Dodgers, perhaps -- blocks the 
Braves? 
</P>
<P>
	Fueled by Fox money, the Dodgers made free agent ace Kevin Brown  
the first $100 million man in the majors. They also hired Davey 
Johnson, who never has finished lower than second place in 10 full 
seasons as a manager. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a talented team,'' Johnson said. ``My job is to give them  
the best opportunity to win. We have a chance to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta should easily win the East even though it lost first  
baseman Andres Galarraga, who was diagnosed with lymphoma and is 
out for the season. Houston should repeat in the Central despite 
Moises Alou's knee injury in a treadmill accident, which probably 
will keep him out for the year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dodgers should win the weaker West, while the New York Mets  
may take the wild card, beating out Mark McGwire and the St. Louis 
Cardinals. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chicago Cubs, who earned the extra playoff spot last year  
behind Sammy Sosa, lost their chance in March when Kerry Wood was 
sidelined for the season with an elbow injury. 
</P>
<P>
	A look at the NL in predicted order of finish: 	
</P>
<P>
                               *EAST 	
</P>
<P>
                          *Atlanta Braves    	
</P>
<P>
	Greg Maddux, Tom Glavine, Smoltz &AMP; Co. will surely be back in  
the playoffs. The only question is how far they will go. 
</P>
<P>
	GM John Schuerholz acted quickly to fill Atlanta's biggest  
needs, signing free agent RF Brian Jordan (.316, 25 HRs, 91 RBIs 
for St. Louis) to boost the offense and trading for Cincinnati 2B 
Bret Boone (95 RBIs) to steady the infield. 
</P>
<P>
	For now, Ryan Klesko (18 HRs, 70 RBIs) moves from LF to take  
over at 1B for Galarraga (.305, 44, 121). New batting coach Don 
Baylor also intends to improve Klesko's hitting. 
</P>
<P>
	As always, the rotation is as ripe as the juiciest Georgia  
peach. Glavine (20-6, 2.47 ERA) kept the Cy Young Award in Atlanta, 
while Maddux (18-9, 2.22), Smoltz (17-3, 2.90) and Kevin Millwood 
(17-8) were impressive. Impressive in camp, 20-year-old LH Odalis 
Perez beat out rookie LH Bruce Chen for the spot left by Denny 
Neagle. 
</P>
<P>
	The bullpen may be a trouble spot. Kerry Ligtenberg (30 saves)  
is out after injuring an elbow in a spring game, meaning John 
Rocker (2.13 ERA, 47 games) might be the closer. Former ace Mark 
Wohlers seems to have made progress in solving a control problem 
that threatened to end his career. 
</P>
<P>
                           *New York Mets    	
</P>
<P>
	A whirlwind winter has Mets fans hoping this will be the year  
their team wins a postseason game for the first time since Keith 
Hernandez and Gary Carter played in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	LF Rickey Henderson (101 runs for Oakland) led the majors with  
66 steals at age 40. He'll bat leadoff in a lineup that added 3B 
Robin Ventura (91 RBIs for the White Sox) and RF Bobby Bonilla. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Piazza (.328, 32, 111) begins his first full season as the  
main man at Shea Stadium, supported by John Olerud (.354, 93 RBIs). 
Edgardo Alfonzo moves to 2B to make room for Ventura. 
</P>
<P>
	Al Leiter (17-6, 2.47) and Rick Reed (16-11) lead a rotation  
that is solid, not spectacular. John Franco (0-8, 38 saves) often 
was shaky, and the Mets hope Armando Benitez (87 strikeouts in 68 
1-3 innings for Baltimore) settles down. 
</P>
<P>
	Bobby Valentine has gone 1,541 games (769-772) without a playoff  
appearance, the longest drought at the start of a career by any 
manager in 40 years. At least he won't have to hear fired announcer 
Tim McCarver talk about it. 
</P>
<P>
                       *Philadelphia Phillies    	
</P>
<P>
	Topic No. 1 in town is still Curt Schilling. As in, will the  
Phillies trade their ace? 
</P>
<P>
	GM Ed Wade insists Schilling (15-14, major league-leading 300  
strikeouts) is staying, saying Philadelphia wants to build around 
him. If so, he'll lead a staff that underwent a lot of change -- 
Chad Ogea, Paul Spoljaric and Jeff Brantley came, while Ricky 
Bottalico, Mark Leiter and Mark Portugal left. 
</P>
<P>
	3B Scott Rolen (.290, 31, 110) is among the best young players  
in the game. Rico Brogna (104 RBIs), Bobby Abreu (.312) and Doug 
Glanville (23 SBs) did well. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark down May 10. That's when newcomer Ron Gant (26 HRs) faces  
Tony La Russa's team for the first time since implying his former 
St. Louis manager had different standards based on race. 
</P>
<P>
                          *Montreal Expos    	
</P>
<P>
	The good news in Montreal: For the first time in years, the  
Expos kept all of their young stars during the offseason. The bad 
news: The city might be losing its whole team because of shaky 
finances. 
</P>
<P>
	Felipe Alou, perhaps the most patient man in all of baseball,  
turned down a chance to manage the Dodgers and stuck around. He has 
the next Clemente or Griffey -- depending on whose opinion is asked 
-- in 23-year-old RF Vladimir Guerrero (.324, 38, 109). 
</P>
<P>
	Ugueth Urbina (34 saves, 1.30 ERA) might be the most unhittable  
reliever in the majors, but not that many people know it. 
</P>
<P>
                          *Florida Marlins    	
</P>
<P>
	As predicted, the Marlins set a record for the worst record by a  
defending World Series champion -- 54-108. The Florida forecast 
calls for a bright future, although it may be a few years away. 
</P>
<P>
	First-year manager John Boles inherits from Jim Leyland a young  
staff that has promise. Add in 1997 World Series MVP Livan 
Hernandez (10-12, 4.72) and Alex Fernandez's return from rotator 
cuff surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	Reliever Braden Looper, acquired from St. Louis for Edgar  
Renteria, is among the young talent. So is rookie 3B Mike Lowell, 
recovering from testicular cancer. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
                             *CENTRAL   	
</P>
<P>
                          *Houston Astros    	
</P>
<P>
	To win its third straight Central title and close out the  
Astrodome in style, Houston must overcome two huge losses -- Randy 
Johnson to free agency, and Moises Alou to a knee injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Fortunately, the ``Killer B's'' are still intact with Jeff  
Bagwell (.304, 34, 111), Craig Biggio (.325, 50 SBs) and Derek Bell 
(.314, 108 RBIs). 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Hidalgo (.303) will fill in for Alou (.312, 38, 124),  
while former MVP Ken Caminiti (29 HRs) returns from San Diego. 
</P>
<P>
	Shane Reynolds (19-8), Jose Lima (16-8) and 23-year-old Scott  
Elarton -- the pitcher Houston would not trade for Roger Clemens -- 
get plenty of help from a deep bullpen led by Billy Wagner (30 
saves, 97 strikeouts in 60 IP). 
</P>
<P>
	The most wondrous stadium in America when it opened in 1965 --  
Mickey Mantle hit the first home run in an exhibition -- the 
Astrodome never has held the World Series. Coming off a team-record 
102 wins, this is Houston's last chance before moving into The 
Ballpark at Union Station in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
                        *St. Louis Cardinals    	
</P>
<P>
	Mark McGwire and his 70 home runs brought the whole country's  
attention to Busch Stadium in 1998. Only a healthy pitching staff, 
however, will bring the playoffs to St. Louis in 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	And it's not looking good. Matt Morris, expected to be the ace,  
will miss the season because of an elbow injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Morris, Alan Benes and Donovan Osborne were hurt last year,  
leaving Kent Mercker (11-11) as the top winner and only pitcher to 
make 25 starts. Manny Aybar and Darren Oliver should bolster the 
rotation, while Juan Acevedo (2.56 ERA, 15 saves) is joined in the 
bullpen by former All-Star Ricky Bottalico, injured last year in 
Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire (147 RBIs, 162 walks) and Ray Lankford (31 HRs, 105  
RBIs) are joined by free agent OF Eric Davis (.327, 28, 89) and SS 
Edgar Renteria (.282, 41 SBs). Renteria and Lankford, though, were 
slowed this spring by bad knees. 
</P>
<P>
	Plus, there's J.D. Drew. Projected as the 1999 Rookie of the  
Year, he gave a glimpse of his glorious future by hitting .417 with 
five homers and 13 RBIs in only 36 at-bats as a September call-up. 
</P>
<P>
                          *Cincinnati Reds    	
</P>
<P>
	GM Jim Bowden was busy in the winter, getting Greg Vaughn, Denny  
Neagle, Steve Avery and more. Along the way, he restored some hope 
in Cincinnati, too. 
</P>
<P>
	Vaughn (50 HRs, 119 RBIs for San Diego) is the biggest hitter in  
a lineup that needs SS Barry Larkin (.309, 26 SBs) to stay healthy. 
</P>
<P>
	Pete Harnisch (14-7) and Neagle (16-11 for Atlanta) were hurt  
this spring and Avery (10-7 for Boston) has been injured in past 
years. Reliever Stan Belinda (4-8) is pitching even though he was 
diagnosed with multiple sclerosis. 
</P>
<P>
                           *Chicago Cubs    	
</P>
<P>
	Minus Kerry Wood, the oldest team in the league is sure to  
extend baseball's oldest drought -- the Cubs have not won the World 
Series since 1908. 
</P>
<P>
	Chicago started this spring full of excitement, coming off MVP  
Sammy Sosa's 66-homer season and its one-game playoff win over San 
Francisco for the wild-card spot. All that enthusiasm was dashed 
when Wood was lost for the season, and possibly longer, because of 
elbow damage. 
</P>
<P>
	Sosa (.308, 158 RBIs), Mark Grace (.309), Henry Rodriguez (31  
HRs) and latecomer Gary Gaetti (70 RBIs) made Wrigley Field a fun 
place last fall. Without the 21-year-old Wood, who struck out 20 
Houston hitters in a May game, it should be a long summer 
</P>
<P>
	Kevin Tapani (19-9, 4.85) is now 35, and every player in the 	
starting lineup will be over 30 after the All-Star break. The Cubs 
signed Hideo Nomo to a minor league contract after he was cut by 
the Mets. 
</P>
<P>
                        *Pittsburgh Pirates 	
</P>
<P>
	Eager to boost a lineup that was next-to-last in NL scoring, the  
Pirates got Brian Giles, Brant Brown and Ed Sprague. Their most 
curious trade, though, comes in the leadoff spot: Jason Kendall, 
now batting instead of traded Tony Womack. 
</P>
<P>
	Kendall (.327, .411 on-base percentage) could become the first  
catcher in major league history to hit leadoff on an everyday 
basis. He set an NL record for catchers by stealing 26 bases, yet 
he must stay healthy -- he was hit by a pitch 31 times last year, 
most in the majors. 
</P>
<P>
	For those curious: Since 1970, Jeff Newman (32) and Butch  
Wynegar (31) are the only catchers to bat leadoff more than 30 
times in a season. 
</P>
<P>
	Francisco Cordova (13-14, 3.31) leads a young rotation that  
pitched better than the records show. 
</P>
<P>
                         *Milwaukee Brewers    	
</P>
<P>
	This is the Brewers' final year at County Stadium before they  
move into Miller Park. It might also be manager Phil Garner's last 
try at stopping a rut of six straight losing seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Unfortunately, Garner does not have much to work with. Jeromy  
Burnitz (38 HRs, 125 RBIs) led the hitters and no pitcher won more 
than 10 games. Maybe Jim Abbott can help in both areas -- 5-0 for 
the White Sox last year, he showed skill at the plate in spring 
training despite having only one hand. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
                               *WEST    	
</P>
<P>
                        *Los Angeles Dodgers    	
</P>
<P>
	Davey Johnson's job is easily defined: Help the Dodgers win a  
postseason game for the first time since Orel Hershiser beat 
Oakland in Game 5 to win the 1988 World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dodgers gave Brown (18-7, 2.38) a $105 million, seven-year  
contract and hope he will work his magic on and off the mound -- 
he's credited with inspiring pitchers in Florida and San Diego 
during the past two seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Ismael Valdes (11-10, 3.98), Chan Ho Park (15-9, 3.71), Darren  
Dreifort (8-12, 4.00) and Carlos Perez could all benefit from being 
around Brown. Jeff Shaw (48 saves overall) is fine. 
</P>
<P>
	Runs should be no problem. In Johnson's previous three positions  
-- with Baltimore, Cincinnati and the Mets -- his team's offense 
dramatically improved in his first full season. 
</P>
<P>
	As much as anything, the Dodgers need former All-Star C Todd  
Hundley (.161) to recover from elbow surgery that limited him to 53 
games for the Mets. Gary Sheffield (.302) griped this spring about 
moving from right field to left, while newcomer Devon White should 
settle things in center field. 
</P>
<P>
                        *San Francisco Giants    	
</P>
<P>
	Somehow, Dusty Baker keeps finding ways to win. Of course,  
having Barry Bonds on his side helps. 
</P>
<P>
	With Bonds (.303, 37, 122, 28 SBs) and Jeff Kent (.297, 31, 128)  
leading the way, the Giants made it to a one-game playoff before 
losing to the Cubs. 
</P>
<P>
	Now going into the final season of what used to be called  
Candlestick Park, the Giants may find it difficult to duplicate 
last year's 89 victories. Most of all, they need former ace Shawn 
Estes (7-12, 5.06) to fully recover from arm woes. Kirk Rueter 
(16-9) and Mark Gardner (13-6) get relief from Robb Nen (40 
saves). 
</P>
<P>
                         *Colorado Rockies    	
</P>
<P>
	Jim Leyland comes to Coors Field facing a formidable and  
familiar task in Colorado -- trying to find enough pitching. 
</P>
<P>
	Sure, the Rockies boast NL batting champion Larry Walker (.363,  
23 HRs), Vinny Castilla (.319, 46, 144), Dante Bichette (.331, 22, 
122) and young Todd Helton (.315, 25, 97). Yet as their 77 wins 
show, it takes more than hitting. 
</P>
<P>
	Darryl Kile (13-17, 5.20) found out the hard way. After going  
19-7 with a 2.57 ERA for Houston, he signed with Colorado and got 
knocked around. Further evidence came last summer when the AL beat 
the NL 13-8 in the highest-scoring All-Star game. 
</P>
<P>
                       *Arizona Diamondbacks    	
</P>
<P>
	Randy Johnson gives the Diamondbacks a presence rarely seen in  
second-year franchises. Yet for all of owner Jerry Colangelo's 
spending, Arizona may not greatly improve on its 65 wins. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson (10-1, 1.28 for Houston), Todd Stottlemyre (14-13  
overall) and Armando Reynoso join surprising Omar Daal (8-12, 2.88) 
and Andy Benes (14-13) in the rotation. Gregg Olson may be 
hard-pressed to duplicate his 30 saves. 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona hit a major league-worst .246, and Steve Finley, Luis  
Gonzalez and two-time NL stolen base champion Tony Womack will not 
boost that a lot. Young 1B Travis Lee (22 HRs) is improving, but 
the D-backs need much more from Matt Williams (20 HRs, 71 RBIs). 
</P>
<P>
                          *San Diego Padres    	
</P>
<P>
	Tony Gwynn and his Padres put it all together last season,  
reaching the World Series and winning voter approval for a new 
ballpark. Then, much like the 1997 champion Marlins, they were 
gutted. 
</P>
<P>
	Kevin Brown, Greg Vaughn, Steve Finley, Ken Caminiti and others  
are all gone, making country music star Garth Brooks the most 
interesting attraction in camp this spring. The result: San Diego 
could become the first team to go from last to first to last again. 
</P>
<P>
	Gwynn (.321) needs 72 hits to reach 3,000. At 39, he could be  
joined in that exclusive club this year by Wade Boggs and Cal 
Ripken. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
