<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 13:52:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sonics Fall Flat Without Baker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- There's a morsel of good news for the  
Seattle SuperSonics in what has been their most disappointing 
season of the '90s: Vin Baker is getting close to returning. 
</P>
<P>
	Without the injured 6-foot-11 forward, the Sonics have gone from  
decent to dreadful. Until he returns, they don't have much of a 
game plan. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't just say, `I wish Michael Jordan would come to my  
team,' '' Gary Payton said after Seattle's 107-95 loss to the 
Portland Trail Blazers Friday night, which ended a 1-4 road trip. 
``It won't happen. So right now, hopefully, we can start playing a 
little better, and when (Baker) gets back, we hope that he can 
produce quickly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The loss dropped the Sonics to 15-16, a startling decline for a  
team that won four Pacific Division titles in the past five years 
and averaged 59 1/2 wins between 1992 and 1998. Seattle hasn't been 
below .500 this late in the season since 1990-91, when they 
finished 41-41. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not happy about being below .500,'' coach Paul Westphal  
said. ``We've got a chance, going home, to do something about it. 
We are undermanned, but I like the fight we've shown.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baker began the season overweight and out of sync, and was  
ridiculed when he missed his first 18 foul shots. But the Sonics 
started 6-0, and Baker gradually improved. He scored 31 points and 
tipped in the winning basket in an 87-85 victory at Vancouver March 
16. The Sonics had won three straight and were 12-9. 
</P>
<P>
	In his next game, Baker injured his right thumb in a loss at  
Golden State. He played only 11 minutes in a loss at Denver two 
nights later, and was put on the injured list with a partially torn 
ligament in the thumb. 
</P>
<P>
	Without him, the Sonics are 2-5, and the lack of muscle in the  
middle was apparent against the Blazers. Seattle didn't make an 
inside shot until Jelani McCoy's layup early in the second quarter. 
The Sonics also were outrebounded 45-35. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you're without your All-Star low-post player, you  
struggle to find your inside game, and you struggle to defend 
inside,'' Westphal said. 
</P>
<P>
	The injury to Baker has taken some of the heat off Westphal, who  
replaced the fired George Karl and stood to take much of the blame 
for the Sonics' letdown this season. But the reality is that many 
of Seattle's problems have nothing to do with either Baker or 
Westphal. 
</P>
<P>
	Shooting guard Hersey Hawkins has lost his confidence, even  
suggesting that Westphal bench him following a 104-87 loss at 
Detroit last week. He's averaging a career-low 9.2 points, and is 
shooting 26 percent from 3-point range, compared to 42 percent last 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sonics have been starting Billy Owens at shooting guard  
lately, and it's not working. In a 113-110 loss to the Nuggets 
Thursday night, Chauncey Billups lit up Owens for a career-high 32 
points. Isaiah Rider took his turn against Owens Friday night, 
hitting all six of his first-quarter shots for 13 of his 23 points. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sonics are 4-12 on the road, with six of the losses coming  
with a healthy Baker in the lineup. Also, Seattle's bench has been 
weakened by the retirement of Nate McMillan and the loss of free 
agents Jerome Kersey and Greg Anthony. 
</P>
<P>
	Anthony, who signed with the Blazers, helped shut down the  
Sonics in the stretch Friday night, forcing them into 10 turnovers 
in the fourth quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	``Never have I seen so many turnovers in one quarter,''  
Seattle's Detlef Schrempf said. 
</P>
<P>
	Baker, wearing a soft cast, took a few shots during warmups at  
Denver, and worked against Seattle's big men before the Portland 
game. He was supposed to be on the injured list for at least four 
weeks, but said he wanted to play Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he's dreaming,'' Westphal said. ``If the team doctor  
says no, Vin doesn't have any say. If the team doctor says it's up 
to Vin, then we'll see.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Payton, who hasn't endured a losing season as a pro or in  
college at Oregon State, wishes his teammate a quick recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't know, when he gets back, what's going to happen,''  
Payton said. ``We can't just say, `Vin, can you give us 30?' It's 
not going to happen. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope things get better, and right now they're not.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
