<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Severe storms pounded the central part of the nation today,  
while the East Coast and far Southwest were mostly dry. 
</P>
<P>
	Showers and thunderstorms were expected to spread from the Great  
Lakes all the way down to the Gulf Coast, with particularly strong 
storms in the southern Plains and lower Mississippi Valley. High 
winds and large hail were possible. 
</P>
<P>
	Snow and windy conditions were forecast to the north and west of  
the storm system. Accumulations of six inches were possible in the 
Dakotas, with higher amounts likely in the Rockies from Wyoming to 
Arizona and New Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the storm began Thursday, Lander, Wyo., has recorded 2  
feet of snow with winds gusting over 40 mph. Hundreds of North 
Dakotans were without power Friday as the state cleaned up from 
heavy snowfall. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pacific Northwest should see showers along the coast and  
snow at higher elevations. Farther south in California, dry and 
partly cloudy conditions were forecast, except for some snow in the 
Sierra Nevada. 
</P>
<P>
	Most areas of the East should be dry with partly cloudy skies. A  
few rain showers were possible late today in the eastern Great 
Lakes. 
</P>
<P>
	The highest temperature in the continental United States on  
Friday was 88 degrees in Wink, Texas. The low was 4 degrees at 
Yellowstone, Wyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Highs today were forecast to reach the 20s and 30s in the  
northern Rockies and upper Plains; 40s and 50s in the Northwest; 
50s and 60s in the Northeast and desert Southwest; 60s and 70s in 
the central Plains; and 70s and 80s in the Southeast and southern 
Plains. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
