<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sixers' Iverson Skips Road Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Allen Iverson, hobbled by injury and mired  
in a feud with 76ers coach Larry Brown, did not make a road trip to 
Toronto with the team Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Iverson, who exchanged words with Brown and sat out the last  
three quarters of an 85-80 loss to Cleveland on Friday night, 
stayed in Philadelphia to get treatment on a strained and severely 
bruised right quadriceps, team spokeswoman Karen Frascona said. 
</P>
<P>
	Iverson, the NBA's leading scorer, will be re-evaluated Monday  
and is listed as day-to-day. 
</P>
<P>
	The prolific, sometimes volatile superstar has had a rocky  
relationship with Brown since the coach arrived last season. With a 
scintillating start this season for Iverson and the team, both 
proclaimed their differences behind them. 
</P>
<P>
	But the old animosity flared up for all to see Friday night.  
</P>
<P>
	Iverson was benched for the opening 2:03 of the second quarter  
after going 0-for-7 in the first quarter. When Brown told Iverson 
to go back into the game, Iverson muttered something that reporters 
sitting near the Sixers' bench reported as, ``It's about ... time 
you put me back in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The exchange was heard by reporters who sit courtside between  
the Sixers' bench and the scorer's table, where Iverson had been 
ready to check in. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown pulled him out again, and Iverson sat the rest of the  
game. Iverson didn't even participate in halftime warmups or sit on 
the bench until the third quarter was under way. 
</P>
<P>
	The team's official explanation was a strain to a right thigh  
that already had been severely bruised in a collision with the 
Lakers' Shaquille O'Neal on Feb. 19. 
</P>
<P>
	Iverson said he was not going to play at Toronto on Sunday and  
was doubtful for Tuesday's home game against Milwaukee because of 
his thigh. Brown and Iverson agreed that he should not make the 
trip. 
</P>
<P>
	``It hasn't gotten any better,'' Iverson said. ``I've never had  
anything like this before. Ever. ... It feels the same as when I 
first did it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brown, without mentioning Iverson by name, questioned his  
players' maturity and whether winning was their primary focus in a 
postgame press conference. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think mature guys who care about their teams step up,''  
Brown said. ``I don't think we have that maturity yet. ... I'm the 
coach and I have the right to play a guy or not play a guy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The dispute raised old questions about Iverson's compatibility  
with his coach. A year ago, Brown urged Iverson to become more of a 
playmaker instead of a shooter, publicly criticizing Iverson's 
running of the team, his defense and his off-the-court lifestyle. 
</P>
<P>
	Iverson responded by vowing he would ``remember everything come  
contract time'' -- although in January he signed a six-year, $70.9 
million contract extension. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, Iverson had an unexcused absence from practice March 11.  
In a brilliant move that forced Iverson to be accountable to his 
teammates, Brown had the team decide how to handle it. Brown 
followed the players' recommendation not to suspend Iverson, but 
the 23-year-old guard was warned that further transgressions would 
be punished. 
</P>
<P>
	Iverson tried to downplay Friday's quarrel.  
</P>
<P>
	``There ain't no problems,'' he said after the game.  
``Everything ain't going to be peaches and cream all the time. But 
I don't have any problems with him.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
