<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Troops May Enter Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- NATO said today an international,  
alliance-led force could go into Kosovo to return refugees ahead of 
any signing by Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic of a Kosovo 
peace agreement. Until now, NATO was planning for a peacekeeping 
force on the ground in Kosovo only after compelling Milosevic to 
enter a peace agreement with the Kosovo Albanians. A NATO source 
said it was the first time the alliance was considering such a 
force without Milosevic first signing the draft agreement signed by 
Kosovo Albanians at peace talks in Rambouillet, France. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton: No Target Is Off-Limits  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration declared today that  
``no target is off-limits'' in the campaign to pressure Serb forces 
to end their campaign of repression in Kosovo. President Clinton, 
in his weekly radio address, declared the Kosovo operation ``a 
difficult and dangerous one, but it's necessary and right, and we 
must stand with all our NATO allies to see it through.'' Clinton 
also said the U.S. military would pitch in with humanitarian relief 
for what NATO spokesman Jamie Shea today called a ``demographic 
earthquake'' in the Balkans -- with 290,000 refugees having left 
Kosovo in the past 10 days and 300,000 more moving toward the 
border. 

</P>
<P>
	Enraged Belgraders Curse NATO  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Enraged Belgraders cursed NATO today  
for attacking the heart of Yugoslavia's capital, while Western 
leaders made plans to airlift emergency supplies and send troops to 
help hundreds of thousands of Kosovo Albanian refugees overwhelming 
bordering regions. NATO cruise missiles destroyed the downtown 
Belgrade headquarters of some of President Slobodan Milosevic's 
security forces before dawn, escalating the mission to stop a 
terror campaign against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Germany Prepares for Kosovo Role  
</P>
<P>
	AMBERG, Germany (AP) -- With the debate in NATO over sending  
ground troops into Kosovo growing, Germans used to watching their 
soldiers sit out allied operations because of World War II 
inhibitions are nervously preparing to do their part this time. 
Three thousand German soldiers are already in Macedonia, a quarter 
of the NATO force on standby there to monitor a hoped-for peace 
agreement. Germany's Nazi past fostered strong pacifist sentiments 
that kept the German army at home for decades. Still, a recent poll 
found 62 percent of Germans supported the army's participation in 
the NATO action, while 31 percent opposed it. 

</P>
<P>
	Farmers Urged To Prepare for Cuts  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Facing a dim agricultural forecast this year,  
farm families should begin now to assess their financial situation 
and adjust their spending habits, advises Janet Bechman, a Purdue 
University extension specialist in consumer sciences. Last year's 
price collapse has affected agricultural commodities from grains to 
livestocks. Forecasts for this year project little improvement as 
the Asian economic crisis continues and the market for U.S. goods 
abroad declines. The Agriculture Department predicts net farm 
income for 1999 will drop $3.4 billion, to $44.6 billion. 

</P>
<P>
	China Dissidents Appeal To U.S.  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- A member of a banned Chinese opposition party has  
written to President Clinton urging him to mention the beleaguered 
party's plight when he meets with China's premier in Washington. 
Gao Hongmin, in a letter dated today and faxed to The Associated 
Press, asked Clinton to encourage Premier Zhu Rongji to back human 
rights improvements that would give Chinese freedom to voice their 
opinions and form opposition parties. Zhu leaves Tuesday for a trip 
to the United States and Canada. 

</P>
<P>
	NYC Protesters Won't Be Charged  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Prosecutors plan to drop charges against the  
1,200 people arrested at protests sparked by the police shooting of 
an unarmed West African immigrant. Amadou Diallo, a street vendor 
from Guinea, was killed Feb. 4 outside his Bronx apartment when 
four police officers fired 41 shots and struck him 19 times. The 
shooting led to daily demonstrations outside police headquarters in 
Manhattan where a number of prominent activists were arrested. 

</P>
<P>
	Report: Second Offer Made for Reds  
</P>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Marge Schott reportedly has a second offer for  
her controlling shares in the Cincinnati Reds and Schott's limited 
partners appear to be willing to exercise their option to acquire 
her shares. The Cincinnati Enquirer and The Cincinnati Post 
reported today that the limited partners, led by financier Carl 
Lindner, have offered to match Cleveland lawyer Larry Dolan's $65 
million offer for most of her shares. Both also reported that Steve 
Schott, a cousin of Marge Schott's late husband, heads a group that 
has made a rival offer. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
