<DOCNO> APW19990403.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 15:51:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Silverbulletday Wins Ashland Stakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- Silverbulletday made her case for a  
Kentucky Derby entry today, coming from off the pace in the 
backstretch at Keeneland to win the $500,000 Ashland Stakes going 
away. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bob Baffert-trained filly ran the 1 1/16 miles in 1:41.72,  
winning by seven lengths over Marley Vale. Gold From The West was 
third. The time was a record for the stakes at its current 
distance. 
</P>
<P>
	Owner Mike Pegram, who looked like he worked up more of a sweat  
than his filly, mopped his brow with a shredded napkin as he ducked 
questions about whether Silverbulletday would try to extend her 
six-race winning streak in the Kentucky Derby on May 1. 
</P>
<P>
	``You all have got to realize the Kentucky Derby is a  
mile-and-a-quarter, and is that in the best interests of the 
filly?'' he said. ``That's what we've got to decide, and I'm glad 
Bobby (Baffert) is going to have to make that decision and not 
me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert was in California at the Santa Anita Derby, watching his  
3-year-old colts General Challenge and Prime Timber finish 1-2 in 
their final Kentucky Derby tuneup. 
</P>
<P>
	Jockey Jerry Bailey said Silverbulletday, who has now won nine  
of 10 lifetime starts, including last year's Breeders' Cup Juvenile 
Fillies, reminded him of an earlier champion mount. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kind of shades of Cigar,'' Bailey said.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was never worried,'' he said. ``In the first turn, she threw  
her ears up and she really got herself into the race. She's as good 
a filly as I've ridden.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sent off as a 1-5 favorite in the six-horse field,  
Silverbulletday paid $2.60, $2.40 and $2.10, Marley Vale $3.60 and 
2.10 and Gold From The West $2.10. 
</P>
<P>
	On a muddy track, Silverbulletday stayed wide around the first  
turn and was three-wide along the backstretch. Marley Vale sprinted 
clear from the start and led by 3 1/2 lengths at the half-mile over 
Gold From The West, with Silverbulletday another four lengths back. 
</P>
<P>
	Bailey pushed Silverbulletday up to challenge around the second  
turn and she caught Marley Vale at the top of the stretch, then 
pulled away. 
</P>
<P>
	``The things as an owner you look at it the way the jockey gets  
off the horse,'' Pegram said. ``I'll never forget when I was here 
last October, when Gary (Stevens) got off Silverbulletday (after 
the Alcibiades Stakes) and he said, `Wow, this filly is special.' 
You know, you've seen the same look on Jerry's face.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pegram won the Kentucky Derby last year with a Baffert-trained  
colt, Real Quiet. He said that experience has kept him from being 
overly eager to run Silverbulletday in the Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I thought this was the last time I was going to have a good  
horse, then, yeah, I'd probably get a little Derby fever,'' he 
said. ``But this sweat is not from Derby fever. This sweat's from 
happiness and seeing this filly run the way that she ran.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If Silverbulletday does not run in the Derby, she will go in the  
Derby eve Kentucky Oaks, Pegram said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will guarantee you guys one thing: She will not run in  
both'' the Oaks and the Derby, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990403.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 06:25:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Twins Held in Family Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KITTRELL, N.C. -- Investigators say they have no idea why twin  
11-year-old boys allegedly opened fire in their family's home, 
killing their father and wounding their mother and sister. 
</P>
<P>
	The twins, whose names were not released, were each charged  
Friday with murder and two counts of assault with a deadly weapon 
after the incident the night before. 
</P>
<P>
	``Both were equally responsible. Both were equally involved,''  
said sheriff's Capt. John C. Shockley. 
</P>
<P>
	William Harvey Bawcum Jr., 46, heard the sound of bullets and  
bounded up the staircase to protect his wife, Shockley said. He was 
shot in the right cheek and throat and died at the scene. 
</P>
<P>
	Sixteen-year-old Robin Bawcum was hit below her right  
collarbone. Her mother, Deborah, 45, was wounded in her right arm. 
</P>
<P>
	Robin Bawcum was in fair condition and Mrs. Bawcum was in good  
condition at Duke University Medical Center late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities say after the shootings, the boys waited for  
officers to arrive. Police were unsure who called 911. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a terrible, bloody mess. There was a lot of blood all  
through the house,'' Shockley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators said they recovered a .32-caliber handgun.  
</P>
<P>
	The sheriff's department had no record of being called to the  
home 35 miles north of Raleigh for domestic disputes, but Shockley 
said after talking to Mrs. Bawcum, investigators ``understand 
they've had problems with school.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neighbors said Bawcum, a technician for the local telephone  
company, was an avid hunter and fishermen, and the boys practiced 
with BB guns on the family's thickly wooded lot. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's where they learned to use guns,'' said Darlynn  
Oxendine, a family friend and a physical education teacher who was 
Robin's basketball and volleyball coach. 
</P>
<P>
	Oxendine, who spent hours consoling Deborah and Robin Bawcum at  
the hospital, said Mrs. Bawcum kept saying, ```He came up to save 
me.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Oxendine said she was shocked by the shootings.  
