<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers Urged To Prepare for Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Facing a dim agricultural forecast this year,  
farm families should begin now to assess their financial situation 
and adjust their spending habits, an expert advises. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes people are kind of vague about where they're  
spending their money,'' said Janet Bechman, a Purdue University 
extension specialist in consumer sciences. 
</P>
<P>
	``They should make sure they write things down and not just base  
their decision on the way they think things are but the way they 
really are,'' said Bechman, one of several Purdue officials who 
gave hog farmers financial advice during a recent tour around 
Indiana. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year's price collapse has affected agricultural commodities  
from grains to livestocks. Hog farmers, for example, have seen 
prices fall to about 8 cents per pounds, the lowest in 40 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasts for this year project little improvement as the Asian  
economic crisis continues and the market for U.S. goods abroad 
declines. The Agriculture Department predicts net farm income for 
1999 will drop $3.4 billion, to $44.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're watching all of our costs of living,'' said John  
Diettrich, who runs a 3,500 acre corn and soybean farm in Tilden, 
Neb., with his wife and two children. 
</P>
<P>
	``You hold off on expenditures. You just don't make expenditures  
that a family normally would.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Good business practices are even more important these days for  
any farm operation, from shopping for the lowest prices and 
figuring out the best time to buy supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers also can adjust their planting patterns and switch to  
more profitable crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Diettrich said his operation normally grows 20 percent soybeans  
and 80 percent corn. This year, the mix is 40 percent soybeans and 
60 percent corn because soybeans have lower production costs, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	As families plot their financial future, parents should involve  
children who are old enough to participate in the discussion, 
Bechman said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just start thinking about what's important to each one or the  
family as a whole,'' Bechman said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once you figure out which is important, it's a little bit  
easier to look at things,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bechman said families must determine what they can do without  
and what that means: cutting back on a child's extracurricular 
activities or going without cable television or vacations. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of looking at what you're doing, looking at the  
reason you're doing it and seeing if there might be a less 
expensive alternative,'' Bechman said. ``It's saying, 'the reason 
we do this recreation stuff is so we can all be together but do we 
need to go to Disney World so we can all be together.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	Whatever families decide, the decisions should come earlier  
rather than later. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's one of those things where the longer you put it off, the  
more drastic changes you have to make,'' Bechman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
