<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Koznick Wins Final NorAM Slalom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEND, Ore. (AP) -- World Cup veteran Kristina Koznick of  
Burnsville, Minn., took the first-run lead Saturday and, despite a 
winter-like snowstorm and 13-degree weather, made it stand up to 
win the final NorAm Cup slalom of the season as U.S. women swept 
the top four places. 
</P>
<P>
	Koznick had a two-run time of 1 minute, 34.87 seconds, .13  
faster than Sarah Schleper of Vail, Colo., who's coming back from a 
knee ligament injury and broken leg in December. Tasha Nelson of 
Mound, Minn., was third and Alex Shaffer of Park City, Utah, 
fourth. 
</P>
<P>
	Uros Pavlovcic of Slovenia, who won the U.S. giant slalom title  
10 days ago, took the final men's NorAm slalom in 1:36.48 with Andy 
LeRoy of Silverthorne, Colo., finishing second to clinch the men's 
slalom title. 
</P>
<P>
	The NorAm women's slalom championship went to Genevieve Simard,  
who finished 12th Saturday. Canadian Jeff Durand, the downhill 
champion and runnerup in super-G behind Scott Macartney of Redmond, 
Wash., won the men's overall title. 
</P>
<P>
	Alison Powers of Fraser, Colo., a downhill and super-G racer,  
clinched the women's overall crown Friday when she also won the 
super-G championship. On Saturday, she was 29th in the slalom. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
