<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New England Paintings Showcased </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- When Dwight Eisenhower became president nearly  
a half-century ago, a jokester said the first sign of a more 
conservative administration came when Abercrombie and Fitch 
displayed a four-button suit -- the style of a half-century before. 
</P>
<P>
	A handsome portrait of a man in a four-button suit hangs in one  
of the first rooms of a show that opened Friday at the National 
Gallery of American Art. 
</P>
<P>
	The exhibit tells how the values of old New England, both  
conservative and liberal, have helped shape U.S. history. For 
people less interested in history, it sugarcoats the lesson with 
paintings by artists from Winslow Homer to Norman Rockwell. 
</P>
<P>
	The four-button man was the Rev. Thomas Wentworth Higginson,  
painted in 1893 by Frank W. Benson, one of uppercrust Boston's most 
admired portraitists. Higginson's conservative background didn't 
keep him from opposing slavery before the Civil War, so radically 
that his parishioners forced him out of his first pulpit. During 
the war he became colonel of the 1st South Carolina Volunteers, the 
earliest regiment of freed slaves in the Union army. 
</P>
<P>
	In the show, his portrait hangs near Augustus St. Gaudens'  
sternly erect statue of ``The Puritan.'' The puritan is holding 
back his cape to reveal a coat of the 1600s with no fewer than 20 
buttons down the front. His left hand clutches a big brass-bound 
Bible, his right a long cudgel. 
</P>
<P>
	There are 173 items: books, photos, posters -- even a piece of  
needlework by Marguerite Zorach and her better-known husband, 
William Zorach. During World War II, he worked on decorating 
federal buildings in Washington. The picture, ``Maine Islands,'' 
shows two nude couples on the rocks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Who wouldn't want to imagine Maine so free, especially so  
mosquito-free, that one could strip down in nature?'' asks Bruce 
Robertson in the show's catalogue. He teaches art history at the 
University of California in Santa Barbara. 
</P>
<P>
	Dealing with the period from the end of the Civil War to the end  
of World War II, the exhibit notes the romantic picture that 
artists often gave to earlier centuries. Sections of the show have 
ironic titles like ``Gilded Age Pilgrims'' and ``The Discreet Charm 
of the Colonial.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A snowy landscape by Grandma Moses is ``determined to bring  
alive the `good old days,''' says the catalog. 
</P>
<P>
	It also tells the story of the industrialization of New England,  
with its huge textile and shoe factories, its de-industrialization 
as other parts of the country competed successfully -- and its 
re-industrialization after World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	There are photos of a mill girl of 1895 with demure face and  
filthy apron, applying dye to shoes; of Italian immigrant boys 
playing in front of Paul Revere's house; and dreary cityscapes with 
stark factories painted by Stuart Davis, Stefan Hirsch and Charles 
Sheeler. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Picturing Old New England: Image and Memory'' will be at the  
National Gallery of American Art through Aug. 22. Admission is 
free. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
