<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ohio Family Displays 'Eggshelland' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LYNDHURST, Ohio (AP) -- The Manolio family of suburban Cleveland  
started collecting eggshells during President Dwight Eisenhower's 
second term. 
</P>
<P>
	Forty years and 44,000 eggshells later, the family is still  
going strong, creating a colored egg display each Easter and 
drawing bigger drive-by crowds each year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our neighbors are very, very nice about it,'' Betty Manolio  
said. ``There has only been one person that complained, and it was 
about the traffic on Ridgebury.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Her five grown children, four in the Cleveland area and one in  
Pittsburgh, still return to the old homestead each spring to help 
with the three-week routine of setting up the display dubbed 
Eggshelland. 
</P>
<P>
	One of seven grandchildren is old enough to help out. The others  
get a wide-eyed chance to watch. 
</P>
<P>
	Where do you come up with more than 3,600 dozen eggs?  
</P>
<P>
	Over the years, friends and relatives have saved about 30,000  
and two Lyndhurst restaurants have donated their shells. 
</P>
<P>
	``My husband and I go in when they get their shipments, about  
once a week, and we drain the eggs. Then they use them for making 
bread, or whatever they need them for,'' Mrs. Manolio said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Manolios use a stick to poke a hole the size of a dime in  
the eggs and empty them. The eggshells are then washed and the 
edges of the holes are trimmed. 
</P>
<P>
	After painting, the shells are stored by color in boxes, with  
250 shells in each box. 
</P>
<P>
	Uncertain spring weather off Lake Erie can be troublesome for  
the display. Snow and rain won't hurt the shells, but wind and hail 
can be damaging. Last year, just before Easter, a hailstorm 
destroyed 10,238. 
</P>
<P>
	The Manolios got the idea for Eggshelland in 1957 when Ron  
Manolio's mother put dyed eggshells on bushes in front of her home. 
</P>
<P>
	``My husband said it was a good idea because no one really does  
anything for Easter,'' Mrs. Manolio said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
