<DOCNO> APW19990403.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 08:15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Trust Funds Build Budget Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Politicians bickering over which party would  
best protect Social Security's huge trust fund are ignoring a dirty 
little secret: More than 100 other, smaller but similar accounts 
routinely are used to make the budget surplus look bigger. 
</P>
<P>
	These other trust funds cover programs from Medicare to the  
construction of a monument to World War II veterans planned for 
Washington. Although most are tiny and obscure, combined they are a 
mighty force. 
</P>
<P>
	Excluding Social Security and its predicted $137 billion surplus  
next year, the nonpartisan Congressional Budget Office expects the 
other trust funds to run a total surplus exceeding $68 billion in 
2000. 
</P>
<P>
	That means next year's expected $133 billion overall federal  
surplus would be a $4 billion deficit without the Social Security 
money -- and a near $73 billion deficit without the money credited 
to other trust funds. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the next decade, the non-Social Security trust funds are  
expected to amass a cumulative surplus of $614 billion, CBO says. 
</P>
<P>
	That number has enormous political significance. It represents  
three-fourths of the $800 billion in non-Social Security surpluses 
Republicans want for tax cuts, and President Clinton and Democrats 
prefer for Medicare and other programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Take that $614 billion out of the equation, and there is little  
left for either party to use for tax cuts or for more spending over 
the next 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would put off the party for a long time,'' said Robert  
Reischauer, former director of the Congressional Budget Office and 
now senior fellow at the liberal-leaning Brookings Institution. 
</P>
<P>
	All year, Republicans and Democrats have sought to portray  
themselves as fervent protectors of Social Security, a widely 
popular program. Tellingly, though, few want to do the same for the 
other trust funds. 
</P>
<P>
	The chairman of the House Transportation Committee, Rep. Bud  
Shuster, R-Pa., persuaded Congress last year to begin spending most 
of the money in the highway trust fund for road building, instead 
of letting it accumulate. He has launched a similar effort this 
year for a fund covering airport and aviation projects. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other hand, Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., has complained  
that the trust funds have been ``looted'' to balance the budget and 
is waging a long-shot campaign to make that illegal. 
</P>
<P>
	Some analysts say, however, lawmakers have no particular reason  
to leave alone many of the trust funds: Their proliferation makes 
it harder to control spending by creating a sense that the covered 
programs are politically sacrosanct. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's harder to rein them in,'' said Scott Hodge, senior fellow  
at the conservative Citizens for a Sound Economy. ``You can lose 
political and budgetary control.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Federal trust funds bear no relation to private trust funds,  
where someone's money is held and managed by somebody else. 
Instead, federal trust funds are accounting devices where money is 
raised and spent for a defined purpose. 
</P>
<P>
	If a trust fund collects more money than it spends, the  
government is credited with a surplus. The excess cash goes to the 
Treasury, which uses it to purchase paper clips, bombs and other 
government needs and when possible to buy down federal debt. In 
return, the trust fund gets a government IOU. 
</P>
<P>
	It is unclear precisely how many trust funds exist. In a report  
last June, the Congressional Research Service cataloged 110. This 
January, the Congressional Budget Office said there are more than 
150. 
</P>
<P>
	Only a handful of them account for almost all the trust fund  
surpluses. Of the $206 billion in trust fund surpluses expected in 
2000, all but $2.5 billion comes from Social Security, Medicare, 
federal civilian and military retirement, railroad retirement, 
unemployment and highways, aviation and mass transit. 
</P>
<P>
	Sources of the money vary.  
</P>
<P>
	Social Security and Medicare's trust funds for hospital  
insurance get their money from payroll taxes deducted from most 
workers' salaries, matched by their employers. 
</P>
<P>
	Others, such as the transportation funds, get money from users  
through taxes on gasoline, airline tickets and such. 
</P>
<P>
	Still other funds are fed by federal money, making them simply  
accounting devices where the government owes itself money. For 
example, the military retirees' fund comes entirely from the 
government, with no employee contributions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
