<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Troops Come Under Fire  
</P>
<P>
	SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) -- NATO-led troops came under  
fire today while destroying the Bosnian portion of a key rail link 
between Serbia and Montenegro. The commander of the NATO-led forces 
in Bosnia, U.S. Gen. Montgomery Meigs, said the stabilization 
force, known as SFOR and which aren't taking part in the attacks on 
Yugoslavia, fired back and that his forces suffered no casualties. 
Bosnian Serb television claimed the SFOR soldiers killed a railway 
guard. The television showed what appeared to be a body lying in 
the grass and a witness saying SFOR soldiers attacked the guard and 
that he did not resist. The Bosnian Serb claim could not be 
independently confirmed. 

</P>
<P>
	Italian Troops Head to Albania  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO ordered thousands of Italian  
troops to Albania today to help feed and shelter refugees pouring 
out of Kosovo in catastrophic numbers. The Italian troops would 
protect a humanitarian relief effort for more than 100,000 refugees 
there. NATO officials didn't specify the size of the Albania 
deployment, but a diplomatic source, speaking on condition of 
anonymity, said the number being mentioned was about 6,000. 

</P>
<P>
	Kosovo Slaughter Shown on Tape  
</P>
<P>
	KUKES, Albania (AP) -- A short video clip smuggled out of Kosovo  
appears to add graphic evidence to the reports of widespread 
slaughter of ethnic Albanians by Yugoslav authorities across the 
province. The video was handed to international media today by 
Melaim Bellanica, who said he hid from Serbs for five days in his 
basement in the village of Velike Krusa while killings and looting 
raged above. Bellanica also carried a list of 26 names of people he 
said were executed in his village by Serb police. 

</P>
<P>
	Macedonia Overwhelmed by Refugees  
</P>
<P>
	BLACE, Macedonia (AP) -- Macedonia announced today it won't  
accept any more refugees unless they can go on to other European 
countries. Lack of toilets and running water have overwhelmed 
efforts by relief agencies to help. NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said 
that as many as 300,000 more refugees were believed to be en route 
to Kosovo's borders. An estimates 65,000 Kosovo Albanians are 
already jammed along the Macedonian border. 

</P>
<P>
	Report: Govt Settles Radiation Suit  
</P>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Families of 90 cancer patients who allege  
their relatives were unknowingly subjected to military-sponsored 
radiation experiments have reached a proposed $5 million 
settlement, The Cincinnati Enquirer reported today. The lawsuit 
alleged terminally ill cancer patients who sought treatment at 
Cincinnati General Hospital between 1960 and 1971 were given 
full-body and partial-body doses of radiation. The suit named the 
hospital and the federal government among defendants. The 
government was included in the suit because the Defense Department 
paid $651,000 for the test results to learn about the effects of 
radiation exposure. 

</P>
<P>
	Diallo Shooting Spurs D.C. March  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Protesters against police brutality turned  
their attention from New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani to 
President Clinton today as some 2,500 demonstrators marched in 
Washington calling for the president and Congress to help combat 
police abuses. Although the rally was intended to call for changes 
to abusive police practices nationwide it was spurred by the 
shooting of Amadou Diallo, which has riveted national attention on 
the troubled New York City Police Department. Buttons, T-shirts, 
fliers and posters with Diallo's picture or name were everywhere in 
the sea of demonstrators. The crowd frequently erupted into simple 
cries of ``Amadou.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Pope Leads Easter Ceremony  
</P>
<P>
	VATICAN CITY (AP) -- Marking the most solemn ceremony of the  
Catholic calendar, Pope John Paul II led clerics in procession 
through a darkened St. Peter's Basilica today, a candle-lit vigil 
for the coming of Easter. Thousands of faithful lit their own 
candles as he passed, filling the boundless darkness with glints of 
light. 

</P>
<P>
	Composer of 'Oliver!' Dead at 68  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Lionel Bart, the lyricist and composer who created  
``Oliver!'' and other musicals, died of cancer today at age 68, his 
family said. The cause of death was not officially announced, but 
Bart's nephew, Michael Pruskin, said he had been treated for 
cancer. Bart played a large role in reviving the English musical at 
a time when American productions dominated London's stages. 

</P>
<P>
	Raptors 87, Wizards 85  
</P>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Kevin Willis had 22 points and 11 rebounds as the  
Toronto Raptors won their fifth straight game with a 87-85 victory 
over the visiting Washington Wizards today. Rookie Vince Carter had 
18 points and Doug Christie had 14 for Toronto. Mitch Richmond led 
all scorers with 28 points, including 16 in the fourth quarter. Rod 
Strickland had 16 points and Juwan Howard scored 12 and had 10 
boards for Washington. Otis Thorpe had 11 rebounds. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by STEPHANIE GASKELL  
</P>
</TEXT>
