<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Allows N.C. Lighthouse Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ELIZABETH CITY, N.C. (AP) -- A federal judge is not getting in  
the way of the Cape Hatteras Lighthouse and its new resting place 
away from the eroding coastline. 
</P>
<P>
	Dare County, which covers most of the Outer Banks, sued in  
January to stop the move, but Chief U.S. District Judge Terrence 
Boyle ruled Friday he would not stop the project. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the move had already started and it would cost extra  
money to have some the pieces already moved put back. 
</P>
<P>
	``The United States has invested years of effort and millions of  
dollars into the ongoing relocation of the lighthouse,'' he wrote. 
``That relocation is now under way, and significant progress has 
been made.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 208-foot lightouse is the nation's tallest.  
</P>
<P>
	All the outbuildings at the historic light station -- two  
keepers' quarters, three cisterns and an oil house -- have been 
moved to the new location 1,600 feet from the ocean. The 
black-and-white candy-striped lighthouse now stands just 120 feet 
from the Atlantic Ocean. 
</P>
<P>
	As of Friday, the lighthouse's granite foundation has been 50  
percent cut through and removed. 
</P>
<P>
	The beacon is expected to be lifted up on steel runners and  
slowly rolled to its new site by late May or early June. The move 
should be complete by mid-July. 
</P>
<P>
	The beacon once helped sailors navigate the often treacherous  
waters off Cape Hatteras, known as the ``Graveyard of the 
Atlantic.'' It is seldom used today because of the availability of 
high-tech navigation aids. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
