<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Firms Seek Safer Computer Networks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stung by the fast-spreading Melissa computer  
virus, corporate security experts are hoping to deploy new tools to 
protect networks from intruders, including technology that 
automatically identifies and expunges viruses before they cause 
widespread damage. 
</P>
<P>
	Melissa, a particularly insidious virus, infected more than  
100,000 computers and overloaded the e-mail systems of companies 
and government agencies worldwide. Standing out from the roughly 
40,000 other computer viruses already identified, the lightning 
spread of Melissa and several mutant versions underscored a new 
vulnerability in Internet communications. 
</P>
<P>
	Melissa tricks computer users by disguising itself as an e-mail  
from a friend or colleague and comes a note saying that an 
important document is attached. Once the victim opens up the 
document, a Microsoft Word file, the virus digs into the computer's 
Microsoft Outlook address book and sends the same e-mail to the 
first 50 names it finds. 
</P>
<P>
	By Friday, companies said they had largely eradicated the virus  
by upgrading computers with new cures. Federal authorities arrested 
a New Jersey man and charged him on Friday with originating the 
Melissa virus. 
</P>
<P>
	But security experts warn that Melissa mutations could easily  
renew the threat posed by viruses transmitted through e-mail. 
</P>
<P>
	Current methods of eradication are too slow for viruses like  
Melissa. Days can pass before a user realizes a computer is 
tainted. Anti-virus software previously installed on computers may 
not work on the new infection, so technicians must install new 
software. By that time, corporate e-mail systems can crash and 
networks grind to a halt. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM and Symantec Corp., which makes Norton anti-virus software,  
are working together on an all-in-one system to dramatically speed 
up detection and cure. Network Associates Inc., maker of the McAfee 
brand of anti-virus software, has a similar project. 
</P>
<P>
	``The system is designed to immunize the world against  
fast-spreading viruses faster than the virus can spread,'' said 
Steve White, head of IBM's anti-virus laboratory in Hawthorne, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	Here's how it would work.  
</P>
<P>
	Symantec software running on a company's desktop computers would  
automatically scan for as-yet-unidentified viruses, unlike 
conventional software that checks for already discovered ones. 
</P>
<P>
	The software does this with up to 90 percent accuracy, in part  
by matching a stored list of suspicious virus characteristics 
against e-mail and files, White said. 
</P>
<P>
	Got a match? The PC automatically sends a version of the  
potential virus across the Internet to a Symantec office in Santa 
Monica., Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	There, IBM mainframes ``trick'' the virus into thinking it's  
running on a desktop computer. The idea is to tempt it to 
replicate, a key virus behavior. Once copies are made, the system 
automatically figures out a cure, and sends it back across the 
Internet to update all of a company's PCs. 
</P>
<P>
	The process takes anywhere from a few minutes to a few hours,  
White says -- compared to potentially days for current methods, 
which involve programmers testing potential cures. A pilot program 
for this new technology starts this summer and the product, called 
a Digital Immune System, is due out next year. Network Associates 
promises its version by this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	Companies with far-flung operations are modernizing their  
computer networks to try to bolster virus protection. 
</P>
<P>
	Bristol Hotels &AMP; Resorts, a Dallas-based chain, is linking its  
120 hotels into a central computer network, by October, that is 
capable of automatically immunizing all the company's 1,800 Windows 
machines without the help of individual technicians. 
</P>
<P>
	While anti-virus companies do a good job of quickly coming up  
with a cure, a big challenge is distributing it before damage is 
done, says Danny Perkins, Bristol's manager of computer networks 
and e-mail. 
</P>
<P>
	For individual users seeking protection against Melissa-like  
viruses, the usual precautions may not be enough. The traditional 
advice is to refrain from opening an attachment sent by a stranger. 
But Melissa and other e-mail-based viruses nearly always bear the 
names of acquaintances and even friends. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, some security experts warn that users shouldn't open an  
e-mail attachment unless completely sure of the contents. ``With 
Melissa, you would never know'' based on the sender, said Carey 
Nachenberg, chief researcher at Symantec's antivirus research 
facility. 
</P>
<P>
	 *---	 
</P>
<P>
 *TICKER:   	
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average finally closed above 10,000  
after three failed attempts, reaching 10,006.78 ... Computer 
Associates is buying rival software maker Platinum Technology 
International for $3.5 billion ... Wal-Mart dethroned Toys R Us as 
the nation's biggest toy retailer ... A jury ordered Philip Morris 
to pay $81 million to the family of a man who died of lung cancer 
after smoking Marlboros for four decades ... Yahoo! agreed to 
acquire Broadcast.com for $6.08 billion, linking the Internet's 
leading supplier of radio and video programs with Yahoo!'s growing 
list of services ... Atlantic Richfield and BP Amoco are merging in 
a $25.6 billion stock deal that will create the world's 
second-largest oil company ... And in yet another merger, CBS is 
buying the leading television syndicator, King World Productions 
Inc., for $2.5 billion. 

</P>
