<HEADLINE> Report: Second Offer Made for Reds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Marge Schott has a second offer for her  
controlling shares in the Cincinnati Reds, according to published 
reports. 
</P>
<P>
	And Schott's limited partners appear to be willing to exercise  
their option to acquire her shares. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cincinnati Enquirer and The Cincinnati Post, citing  
unidentified sources, reported Saturday that the limited partners, 
led by financier Carl Lindner, have offered to match Cleveland 
lawyer Larry Dolan's $65 million offer for most of her shares. 
</P>
<P>
	Both also reported that Steve Schott, a cousin of Marge Schott's  
late husband, heads a group that has made a rival offer. 
</P>
<P>
	A call to Schott's home was not answered.  
</P>
<P>
	The Cincinnati auto dealer has controlled the Reds since  
December 1984, when she paid an estimated $25 million for her 
shares. She agreed in November to seek a buyer for her controlling 
interest rather than face another suspension from baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	The current ownership agreement expires at the end of 2000, at  
which time the limited partners can oust Schott if she hasn't 
already sold control of the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Schott, 70, owns 6 1/2 shares in the team, including the two that  
make her the managing partner. The limited partners own the other 
8 1/2 shares. 
</P>
