<DOCNO> APW19990403.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 12:12:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Phils' Manager Remembers Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOOVER, Ala. (AP) -- Once Terry Francona walked onto the field at  
the Hoover Met, he knew it would only be a matter of minutes before 
the first Michael Jordan question was asked. 
</P>
<P>
	``What was he like? Did he listen to you? Was it fun managing  
him?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Francona, back in Birmingham for the first time since leaving  
the Barons organization after the 1995 season, expected questions 
about the year he spent managing Jordan. 
</P>
<P>
	Sitting in the visitors dugout Saturday, Francona didn't mind  
the questions. But when asked if managing Jordan ``got you where 
you are now,'' Francona paused, looking for just the right words. 
</P>
<P>
	``If people want to think that, it's fine,'' Francona said  
before the Phillies played the Baltimore Orioles in their final 
exhibition game of the spring. ``I was the only baseball manager he 
ever had, so it doesn't bother me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But make no mistake, Jordan didn't make Francona's career. If  
anything, he may have nudged it along. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't ask for the attention Michael Jordan brought, but  
that's the way it shook out,'' Francona said. ``I don't resent it, 
though. When you get a break, you take it and try to learn from it 
-- if it was a break.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Francona was in his second season managing the Barons, his third  
overall, when Jordan joined his team in 1994. The Barons had won 
the Southern League title the year before and Francona had been 
selected the minor league manager of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Life was good. He lived down the hill from The Met and jogged to  
work each day. 
</P>
<P>
	Then Jordan arrived and the media crush that followed gave  
Francona a crash course in major league managing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone wanted to talk about Michael Jordan, I wanted to talk  
about the Barons,'' he said. ``I would get to the stadium early and 
every single day there would be someone here who wasn't supposed to 
be here. It taught me to be organized, and I guess you could say I 
learned do things on the run.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Things changed overnight for Francona. Suddenly there were  
crowds of 14,000 and a small army of reporters and television crews 
following his team. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was crazy,'' said Phillies pitcher Doug Glanville, who  
played for Orlando of the Southern League at the time. ``Everywhere 
they went it was packed and this place was always jumping.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a major league atmosphere at a minor league park,''  
Francona said. 
</P>
<P>
	And it got Francona, and they way he handled the situation,  
noticed. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996 he was hired as the Detroit Tigers' third-base coach.  
And when the Phillies needed a replacement for the fired Jim 
Fregosi in 1997, Jordan called Phillies general manager Lee Thomas 
and endorsed Francona. 
</P>
<P>
	Gazing out into left field on Saturday, Francona said he  
wouldn't trade his Jordan experience for anything. 
</P>
<P>
	``I remember it was a Saturday night, late in the season and we  
had 16,000 fans here,'' Francona said. ``Michael hit a home run 
over that left-field fence, it was his first one, and I remember 
the look on his face -- it was like `Ahhh, I did it.' That look made 
it all worth it for me.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990403.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 00:11:42 </DATE_TIME>
