<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> In Indiana, Time Is Relative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- What time you got? In Indiana, the answer  
isn't so simple -- especially this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	When dawn breaks Sunday in the Hoosier state, it might be  
Central Standard Time, Eastern Standard Time or Eastern Daylight 
Time-- depending on where you're standing. 
</P>
<P>
	While most of the nation welcomes daylight-saving time by  
nudging their clocks ahead one hour, most of Indiana will skip the 
switch altogether, keeping their clocks on Eastern Standard Time. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the state -- but not all of it.  
</P>
<P>
	In southeastern Indiana, five breakaway counties will make the  
saving-time switch to keep synchronized with nearby Cincinnati and 
Louisville. 
</P>
<P>
	``So many people work in the Cincinnati area, and we're right on  
the borderline,'' said Ohio County Sheriff Elton Fancher. ``Of 
course, it does cause some confusion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's especially true since Ohio County schools don't make the  
switch, leaving some parents pushing one house clock ahead to 
Eastern Daylight Time and leaving another clock on Eastern Standard 
Time, Fancher said. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're always kind of playing that fast-time, slow-time  
thing,'' said Steve Patz, the county's schools superintendent. 
``Surprisingly enough, it goes off with very few hitches.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Adding to the inconsistency, 10 counties in northwest and  
southwest Indiana keep clocks set to Central time -- and they 
observe daylight-saving time. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress approved daylight-saving time in 1918 to save  
electricity and fuel during World War I. 
</P>
<P>
	Indiana lawmakers have pondered making the change ever since,  
but even now, no change looms. 
</P>
<P>
	When a bill to institute daylight-saving time statewide was  
filed in the state Senate once again this year, Senate President 
Pro Tem Robert Garton promptly assigned it to the Rules Committee -- 
a legislative graveyard. 
</P>
<P>
	Year after year, Garton said, surveys show most Hoosiers are  
opposed to daylight-saving time. 
</P>
<P>
	``Part of the problem is the geographic size of the state, a  
relatively long, narrow state, right on the edge of two time 
zones,'' Garton said. ``So the folks in northwest Indiana and the 
folks in southwest Indiana don't want to be out of sync with the 
rest of the state all year long.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Those against daylight-saving time have often argued that  
setting the clocks ahead would throw cows off schedule, making life 
difficult for farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	But ``cows aren't going to scream and holler if you change your  
clocks one hour,'' said David Byers, a dairy farmer in 
north-central Indiana. Still, he doesn't change his clocks. 
</P>
<P>
	That may hint at the real reason behind Indiana's quirky system,  
said Bob Kraft, the state's director of government relations. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe we don't want to observe daylight-saving time because it  
makes us different,'' Kraft said. ``It's a little bit of pride, I 
think.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990403.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 15:21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mormon Head Decries Serb Actions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Mormon church President Gordon B. Hinckley  
on Saturday condemned Serbian ``atrocities'' in Kosovo while urging 
the faith's members to be tolerant of others despite differences of 
belief. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this moment our hearts reach out to the brutalized people  
of Kosovo,'' Hinckley said in opening the church's 169th Annual 
General Conference in the Tabernacle on Temple Square. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is difficult for us to understand how those who claim to be  
Christians can act so barbarically to those of another faith,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 88-year-old Hinckley, president of The Church of Jesus  
Christ of Latter-day Saints since 1995, did not mention the Serbs 
by name but added, ``I am grateful that we are rushing humanitarian 
aid to the victims of these atrocities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Later, church officials said a shipment of 100 tons of clothing  
and blankets would be shipped Tuesday to Macedonia and distributed 
by Mercy Corps, a Christian relief agency. The Mormon church has 
only 100 members in the Yugoslav Federation. 
</P>
<P>
	Hinckley's blunt condemnation was unusual for the general  
conferences, held each year in April and October. Mormon leaders 
seldom use sermons there to comment directly on current events. 
</P>
<P>
	``We must never forget that we live in a world of great  
diversity,'' Hinckley said. ``The people of the earth are all our 
Father's children, and are of many and varied religious 
persuasions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He urged the faith's more than 10 million members toward greater  
tolerance and respect for others. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have differences of doctrine,'' he said. ``This need not  
bring about animosity or any kind of holier-than-thou attitude.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990403.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 08:15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Detectives Chase 'Old' Murder Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Dave Hatch sits alone, a solitary researcher in  
a library of death. 
</P>
<P>
	The shelves around him hold scores of black vinyl three-ring  
binders, each with a tale of murder unsolved -- the woman raped and 
killed behind the Las Vegas Hilton in 1981, the prostitute murdered 
in her room in 1976, the Boston thug dumped in the desert back in 
1969. 
</P>
<P>
	The names of the dead are typed neatly on the spines of the  
300-plus binders, stark black print on white labels. 
</P>
<P>
	``VICTIM: BRUCE FISHER.''   	
</P>
<P>
	``VICTIM: PATRICIA MARGELLO.''   	
</P>
<P>
	``VICTIM: KIMBLEE ELLINGTON.''   	
</P>
<P>
	Old murders are Hatch's beat; the 27-year police veteran opened  
the Las Vegas Police Department's cold-case squad in July 1997. The 
binders date to 1943; the detective scours each for fresh leads on 
cases long since stale, chasing killers long since convinced they 
had beaten the rap. 
</P>
<P>
	``Smoking guns? Those aren't even a challenge,'' says Hatch,  
whose left bicep sports a skull tattoo. ``These cases are 
challenges. You've got to track everybody down, make sure of what 
they can remember.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Las Vegas, Hatch works alone, but the number of cops doing  
similar jobs is increasing across the country. With the national 
murder rate plunging 28 percent since 1993, and with the 
proliferation of high-tech crime-solving methods, cold-case 
investigators are appearing from Newark to New Orleans, from San 
Antonio to Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch has closed dozens of cases since taking the job --  
``closed'' meaning anything from a suspect's confession to his 
arrest to his death to (in one instance) his turning up in the 
federal Witness Protection Program. 
</P>
<P>
	Other cold-case squads nationwide have racked up similarly  
dramatic numbers, relying on a combination of instinct and evidence 
-- much of it unusual. Dog hairs, a religious conversion, a traffic 
ticket, a 23-year-old fingerprint, a Cajun chef -- all have helped 
resolve antique cases, producing these results: 
</P>
<P>
	--In New York City, the squad has cleared 280 cases in three  
years. A 1980 double murder was solved when a Georgia traffic 
ticket tipped police to the suspect's whereabouts. ``OK, you got 
me,'' the reputed drug dealer said upon his arrest in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	--The Washington cold-case squad, in its first five years, closed  
157 old homicides and several high-profile attempted-murder cases. 
</P>
<P>
	--The Los Angeles squad, formed two years ago, has closed 35  
cases in the last six months. In a 1995 murder, detectives used a 
lab comparison of dog hairs to secure an arrest and indictment. 
</P>
<P>
	--The New Orleans squad, in three years, has solved 113 cases,  
including one prompted by an unsolicited tip from a chef at a local 
restaurant. 
</P>
<P>
	--The Massachusetts state police cold-case squad opened for  
business two years ago, reopening investigations into 25 murders. 
Three arrests have resulted. 
</P>
<P>
	--In Newark, N.J., the cold-case squad opened last September and  
scored an almost immediate hit: arresting a woman for her mother's 
1971 slaying. Two other arrests quickly followed, with several more 
cases on the edge of resolution. 
</P>
<P>
	Newark's two-man detective team approaches its task with almost  
religious zeal. The master book that holds details on murders 
dating to the 1940s is called ``the bible,'' and detectives talk of 
``resurrecting'' forgotten victims. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not up to another human being to snuff out the life of an  
8-year-old child or 80-year-old woman,'' says Detective Rashid 
Sabur. ``That's God's decision. We step in and represent the 
victims, because these people are calling us from the grave.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Those calls can lead to strange places.  
</P>
<P>
	Detective Rick Marks, head of the LAPD squad, reopened a 1995  
murder investigation. Derrick Sims was suspected of murdering his 
girlfriend, but the probe had bogged down. The cold-case squad 
tried a new tactic: They went after Sims' dog. 
</P>
<P>
	The squad took hair samples from the pet pooch; they were  
compared with dog hairs collected from a blanket that was wrapped 
around the victim. After the FBI crime lab scored a match, Sims was 
arrested. He goes on trial for murder later this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The renewed interest in crimes from the past is good news for  
surviving families seeking closure. ``Just as rewarding as putting 
the cuffs on a murderer is telling family members that you have the 
guy who did it,'' says Lt. Ray Ferrari, head of the New York squad. 
</P>
<P>
	The response from suspects contacted years down the road?  
``Surprise'' doesn't quite cover it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I tell them, `Well, we never go away.' Then I add 'em to my  
Christmas card list,'' says Hatch, smiling like the cat that ate 
the homicidal canary. ``There are killers that you always want to 
make sure know you're around, and you're never going away. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's good to let 'em know.''  
</P>
<P>
	Hatch is a typical cold-case investigator -- a veteran who  
investigated some 600 murders during 17 years in homicide at Las 
Vegas PD. The New York squad's officers each have between 15 and 30 
years on the job; in New Orleans, the range is 16 to 23 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch could have been born grizzled. His graying hair features a  
Parris Island buzz cut, with a matching salt and pepper beard. His 
sentences are short, blunt, salty. He is the institutional memory 
of the 14-member homicide division. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is a great resource,'' says Lt. Wayne Peterson, head of the  
Vegas homicide bureau. ``His knowledge and experience make him a 
superior investigator.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Already, Hatch has perused cases between 1943 (three years  
before mobster Bugsy Siegel brought the mob west to The Flamingo 
hotel) and the early '80s. 
</P>
<P>
	There are frustrations: He has opened binders and watched  
misfiled fingerprint cards waft into his lap. One binder held an 
unidentified woman's jewelry -- potentially key evidence. A bag of 
bloody clothes was infiltrated by maggots. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now you've got bug DNA in there,'' Hatch deadpans.  
</P>
<P>
	Such problems are quickly forgotten when Hatch gets his hooks  
into a hot case. 
</P>
<P>
	In December, Hatch was reinvestigating the April 1981 rape and  
murder of a local woman when an unsolicited letter arrived in the 
mail from California. 
</P>
<P>
	``I suspect my ex-husband murdered a woman about 15 years ago,''  
the letter began, quickly getting Hatch's attention. ``I don't know 
her name. She died about a year before I met him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch connected the letter to one of his binders, matching  
victim and details. The letter contained potential new evidence; 
Hatch began poring over the old material. Police are quietly 
putting together a case, hoping to close out the 18-year-old 
murder. 
</P>
<P>
	``So this old case is not such a dead case,'' Hatch says. ``You  
just start looking, and all of a sudden, there you go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Improved technology is a key cold-case component, providing  
crime-solving tools that didn't exist when many of these crimes 
were committed: DNA testing, national fingerprint databases, 
enhanced crime scene forensics, ballistics databases. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a single, bloody fingerprint left 23 years earlier that  
convicted Anthony Lowe. Gerrit Weynands, a 46-year-old Seattle 
timber salesman, was shot once in the back of the neck during a 
February 1973 robbery. He died on the street, his pockets turned 
inside out by the bandit. 
</P>
<P>
	The crime, committed during the Nixon administration, remained  
unsolved until Bill Clinton was in office. Lowe, 45, was arrested 
years after the murder on a drug charge. He was fingerprinted, and 
his prints added to the database. 
</P>
<P>
	When the cold-case squad reopened the Weynands case, they ran  
the old fingerprint through the new database. The result: a match 
and a murder conviction. 
</P>
<P>
	Sometimes it's that simple.  
</P>
<P>
	The San Antonio police posts ``featured cold cases'' on its  
Internet site, hoping that another new investigative tool -- the 
World Wide Web -- can help them in solving crimes. 
</P>
<P>
	A simple point-and-click can turn up details of the Nov. 20,  
1986, murder of Michael S. O'Donnell, gunned down while shooting 
pool inside the Blue Sky Lounge. Tips can come in via e-mail. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Space Age hasn't usurped shoe leather. ``It's still  
knocking on doors, talking to people,'' says Sgt. John Rice of the 
New Orleans squad. ``It's not all technology today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rice recently solved an old case based on a lunchtime tip. ``I  
was talking to a chef I knew, and he introduced me to a man whose 
cousin was killed many years ago,'' Rice recalls. 
</P>
<P>
	Rice interviewed the cousin, who provided new information on the  
slaying. Rice hit the streets and quickly made an arrest; he says 
decisions to cooperate years after the crime are a fairly common 
occurrence for cold-case detectives. 
</P>
<P>
	Call it the ``telltale heart syndrome.''  
</P>
<P>
	``When you're 19, you're invincible,'' Rice says. ``You can't  
tell a young man anything. But people change. As he gets older, as 
he has children, he thinks, `Maybe I ought to come forward.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Newark's Sabur, with partner Keith Sheppard, solved a 1995  
murder when they tracked down an eyewitness -- a former drug dealer. 
She had since gone into rehab and become a born-again Christian; 
she viewed the interview as a chance to atone for past sins, and 
identified the killer. 
</P>
<P>
	``She had a change of heart, thanks to Jesus,'' says a grinning  
Sabur, appreciative of the help. 
</P>
<P>
	That the nation's police officers can now investigate old crimes  
is partially attributable to a drastically decreased crime rate. 
Nationally, murder is down about 28 percent in the last five years; 
overall crime is down 7 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, the figures are even more stunning: A 70-percent  
drop-off in homicides in the last five years. That allowed creation 
of the cold-case squad, a luxury that was once impossible in a city 
with 2,245 homicides in the year 1990, where detectives had just 
four days to clear a homicide before catching another case. 
</P>
<P>
	The story was much the same across the Hudson River in Newark,  
where the 1997 murder rate hit its lowest level in 30 years. One 
year later, the cold-case squad opened for business. 
</P>
<P>
	``Twenty years ago, homicide investigators couldn't invest the  
same quality time,'' explains Newark Police Director Joseph J. 
Santiago. ``But we drastically reduced homicides, and it kept the 
investigators from having to deal at the same pace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Newark squad works in an annex behind City Hall. Its  
existence is still somewhat of a secret within the department; two 
phone calls and several transfers were needed to reach one of its 
detectives. 
</P>
<P>
	But the squad had almost instant success.  
</P>
<P>
	In its first five months, it solved three cases: a 1973 slaying,  
the 1995 born-again Christian case, and the 1971 murder of Maylon 
Johnson. The last case generated headlines when it turned out the 
killer was Ms. Johnson's 14-year-old daughter -- now a 41-year-old 
married woman with three kids of her own. 
</P>
<P>
	With evidence in the 27-year-old case at a premium, the  
detectives focused on the suspect. After an emotional two-hour 
interview, she confessed to the slaying. 
</P>
<P>
	The squads share common woes: witnesses who disappear or die,  
suspects who do the same. Memories are no longer as fresh. Hatch 
said closing out cases can involve just acknowledging that the 
prime suspects are dead, themselves victims of murder. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know 15 murder cases where the four or five principals were  
all killed,'' Hatch says. ``Drug crazies -- everybody involved is 
now dead.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But there are other cases, plenty of them, where the suspects  
are still out there. And as Hatch likes to remind those folks, the 
cold-case squad never goes away. 
</P>
<P>
	``The nice thing about murder,'' Hatch says evenly, ``is there's  
no statute of limitations.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990403.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 07:44:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yanks, Indians Should Top AL in '99 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The American League hasn't offered much suspense in the past  
four years. Don't expect that to change in 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Yankees and Cleveland Indians should already count  
on playing at home in October as the top two division champions. 
Last year's runaway winners have only gotten better. 
</P>
<P>
	The World Series champion Yankees traded for five-time Cy Young  
winner Roger Clemens and the Indians signed free agent Roberto 
Alomar. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're the team to beat and we know that,'' Cleveland's Mike  
Jackson said. ``We're sure they understand we're their team to 
beat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the Indians and Yankees improved, the second-place teams  
in their divisions each lost their best player. 
</P>
<P>
	Albert Belle took his fierce swing and hot temper out of Chicago  
to Baltimore, where he will try to shatter records, not locker 
rooms. And Mo Vaughn left Boston for Anaheim, tilting the balance 
of power in the West to the Angels. 
</P>
<P>
	But don't expect New York or Cleveland to be complacent.  
</P>
<P>
	``The hardest thing to do in sports is to win when everyone  
expects you to,'' said Don Zimmer, the Yankees bench coach who will 
manage the team until Joe Torre returns from prostate cancer 
surgery. ``I have never seen a team face as much pressure as this 
team did going into the playoffs after winning 114 games. And they 
responded.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That they did, beating the Texas Rangers and Cleveland before  
sweeping the San Diego Padres in the World Series on their way to a 
record 125 wins. And expectations won't be any lower this year for 
the best team in baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to get to the World Series, because of who we are and  
what we spend on players,'' Torre said of the team's $85 million 
payroll. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indians feel the same way. After a 46-year playoff drought,  
Cleveland has won the AL Central the past four years but hasn't 
been able to win it all. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we're a team that's decided it's time to go win the  
World Series,'' Sandy Alomar said. ``That's not being cocky, it's 
just assuming a responsibility.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The West again will have the only real pennant race. The  
division boasts some of the game's best offensive players in Juan 
Gonzalez and Rafael Palmeiro (Texas), Vaughn and Tim Salmon 
(Anaheim), and Ken Griffey Jr. and Alex Rodriguez (Seattle). 
</P>
<P>
	Whoever makes the best in-season move to get a pitcher probably  
will win the division. So look for Anaheim, which with the addition 
of Vaughn has a spare outfielder -- either Jim Edmonds or Garrett 
Anderson -- to make the playoffs for the first time since 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	The second-place team in the West will compete with Baltimore,  
Boston and Toronto in the league's fourth race -- for the wild-card. 
The wild-card winner has come from the East all four years and 
don't look for that to change. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blue Jays, without manager Tim Johnson and his Vietnam  
tales, may have the second best rotation in the league and are the 
wild-card favorite. 
</P>
<P>
	A look at the AL in predicted order of finish: 	
</P>
<P>
                               *EAST 	
</P>
<P>
                          *New York Yankees    	
</P>
<P>
	The biggest knock against the Yankees being called one of the  
greatest teams ever last season was that they didn't have a 
surefire Hall of Famer. Well, they do now with Clemens (20-6, 2.65 
ERA, 271 Ks), whom they got for David Wells, Graeme Lloyd and Homer 
Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	Only the Yankees could add the best pitcher in the league to the  
best rotation in the league. Plug Clemens in front of David Cone 
(20-7, 3.55), Orlando Hernandez (12-4, 3.13), Andy Pettitte (16-11, 
4.24) and Hideki Irabu (13-9, 4.06) and there's nothing that can 
keep this team out of the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	The offense should only get better this year -- only Scott  
Brosius (.300 BA, 19 HRs, 98 RBIs) had a career year in 1998. With 
Chili Davis healthy, Chuck Knoblauch comfortable and Jorge Posada 
getting more playing time, the Yankees should easily surpass 100 
wins again. 
</P>
<P>
                         *Toronto Blue Jays    	
</P>
<P>
	Granted the Jays lost Clemens and one of their biggest offensive  
threats in Jose Canseco (.237, 46, 107), but they still have youth. 
</P>
<P>
	With veterans Wells (18-4, 3.49), Pat Hentgen (12-11, 5.17) and  
Joey Hamilton (13-13, 4.27) anchoring a pitching staff that 
includes youngsters Kelvim Escobar (7-3, 3.73) and Chris Carpenter 
(12-7, 4.37), manager Jim Fregosi may have the strongest rotation 
in the league after the Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	Then there's 21-year-old Roy Halladay, who came within one out  
of a no-hitter on the final day of the 1998 season. He could be a 
major contributor by year's end. 
</P>
<P>
	Shawn Green (.278, 35, 100, 35 SBs) and Carlos Delgado (.292,  
38, 115) anchor a lineup that could use another bat in the 
outfield. Look for GM Gord Ash to get that player by trading one of 
his pitchers, maybe Hentgen, for possibly Anaheim's Edmonds or 
Anderson or Detroit's Brian Hunter. 
</P>
<P>
                         *Baltimore Orioles    	
</P>
<P>
	Peter Angelos seems to be following the same blueprint Yankees  
owner George Steinbrenner used during the '80s. The only problem 
is, that was the first decade since the 1910s that the Yankees 
didn't win a World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	At least the Orioles have a wild card to shoot for in 1999.  
</P>
<P>
	Baltimore has developed few young players to inject life into  
one of baseball's oldest teams, instead relying on big free agent 
signings. 
</P>
<P>
	But this offseason's moves should do little more than keep  
Baltimore treading water. The Orioles spent $88.5 million to sign 
Belle, Will Clark and Delino DeShields, but those three were about 
as productive as the departed Palmeiro, Alomar and Eric Davis last 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	The new Orioles combined to hit .310 with 79 homers and 268 RBIs  
last season, essentially the same as the .300-85-266 put up by the 
three players who left. 
</P>
<P>
	The most important addition may be Charles Johnson (.218, 19,  
58), coming off his worst year at the plate and in the field. 
Johnson will be called upon to shore up a pitching staff that 
ranked seventh in the AL last year. 
</P>
<P>
	It will be interesting to watch how Cal Ripken responds to a few  
days off. 
</P>
<P>
                           *Boston Red Sox    	
</P>
<P>
	The Red Sox have gotten rid of any outspoken personalities, most  
notably Vaughn (.337, 40, 115), who left for Anaheim. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year's playoff loss to Cleveland proved the Sox needed at  
least one more bat in the lineup to help Vaughn and Nomar 
Garciaparra (.323, 35, 122). Instead, they lost Vaughn and added 
only Jose Offerman (.315, 7, 66), who's coming off his best year 
but still does not scare opposing managers. 
</P>
<P>
	Garciaparra, slowed in the spring by an arm injury, should get  
few good pitches to hit with Mike Stanley (.256, 29, 79) or Troy 
O'Leary (.270, 23, 83) providing protection. If Boston can stay in 
the wild-card race until July, don't rule out a move for a 
legitimate bat at first base or left field. 
</P>
<P>
	Pedro Martinez (19-7, 2.89) and Tom Gordon (7-4, 46 saves) lead  
a pitching staff filled with many questions, most notably the 
health of Bret Saberhagen (15-8, 3.96) and newly signed Ramon 
Martinez, who could be on the roster by the All-Star break. 
</P>
<P>
                        *Tampa Bay Devil Rays    	
</P>
<P>
	The expansion tag has worn off and now the long process of  
getting to respectability begins. 
</P>
<P>
	While expansion-rival Arizona opened up its wallet for free  
agents, the Devil Rays settled for Canseco to add much needed 
firepower to the lowest scoring team in baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	To be competitive, the Rays need Rolando Arrojo (14-12, 3.56) to  
pitch like the All-Star he was in the first half not the 4-8 
pitcher after the break. Also, Wilson Alvarez (6-14, 4.73) needs to 
bounce back from his worst season. 
</P>
<P>
	Wade Boggs' run for 3,000 hits -- he needs 78 -- should provide  
the most drama for Tampa Bay fans. 
</P>
<P>
                             *CENTRAL   	
</P>
<P>
                         *Cleveland Indians    	
</P>
<P>
	The Indians probably will have 12 former All-Stars on their  
opening day roster and could have one in every spot in the lineup 
if Wil Cordero (.267, 13, 49) starts at DH. 
</P>
<P>
	But to compete with the Yankees in the playoffs, Cleveland still  
needs a No. 1 starter. Kansas City's Kevin Appier, Philadelphia's 
Curt Schilling and Oakland's Kenny Rogers could all be available 
before the trading deadline. If not, manager Mike Hargrove must 
count on RHPs Bartolo Colon (14-9, 3.71) and Jaret Wright (12-10, 
4.72). 
</P>
<P>
	The additions of LHP Ricardo Rincon (2.91, 14 saves) and RHP  
Jerry Spradlin (4-4, 3.53) to a bullpen anchored by Jackson (40 
saves, 1.55 ERA) gives Hargrove a lot of versatility. 
</P>
<P>
	The lineup, featuring 1B Jim Thome (.293, 30, 85), RF Manny  
Ramirez (.294, 45, 145) and CF Kenny Lofton (101 runs, 54 SBs), is 
one of the deepest in baseball. 
</P>
<P>
                          *Detroit Tigers    	
</P>
<P>
	The Tigers upgraded the AL's third-worst offense by adding 3B  
Dean Palmer (.278, 34, 119) and OF Gregg Jefferies (.301, 9, 58). 
</P>
<P>
	With 1B Tony Clark (34, 103), OF Bobby Higginson (25, 85) and 2B  
Damion Easley (27, 100) back, offense shouldn't be manager Larry 
Parrish's biggest worry. 
</P>
<P>
	That will be starting pitching. LHP Justin Thompson (11-15,  
4.05) has recovered from elbow surgery, giving the Tigers two solid 
starters with RHP Brian Moehler (14-13, 3.90). The problem is there 
isn't much behind them in the rotation, though last year's No. 1 
pick Jeff Weaver has been impressive in spring training and could 
be in Detroit before Tiger Stadium closes at the end of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Detroit is so ecstatic about rookie CF Gabe Kapler that they are  
willing to trade Hunter, or possibly Higginson, for pitching. 
</P>
<P>
                         *Chicago White Sox    	
</P>
<P>
	The White Sox went 45-31 after the All-Star game for the second  
best mark in the league. But instead of adding to their team and 
making a playoff run, owner Jerry Reinsdorf bid farewell to Belle 
and 3B Robin Ventura, who combined for 69 homers and 243 RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
	That leaves Frank Thomas (.265, 29, 109), coming off his worst  
year, 2B Ray Durham (.285, 19, 67) and not much else. 
</P>
<P>
	It's gotten so bad that the strength of this team might be the  
pitching staff that posted a league-worst 5.22 ERA last year. 
</P>
<P>
                         *Kansas City Royals    	
</P>
<P>
	The Royals lost their two top run producers, Palmer and  
Offerman, and No. 1 starter, Tim Belcher, and got nothing to show 
for it. 
</P>
<P>
	Don't look for GM Herk Robinson to make the same mistake again.  
He'll probably deal at least one of three players -- RHP Kevin 
Appier, closer Jeff Montgomery (36 saves), 1B Jeff King (.263, 24, 
93) -- before the trading deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	Youngsters OF Carlos Beltran, OF Jeremy Giambi and 2B Carlos  
Febles give fans something to look forward to other than George 
Brett's Hall of Fame induction in July. 
</P>
<P>
                          *Minnesota Twins    	
</P>
<P>
	Never a good sign when you start the season with your best  
players on the trading block. The Twins would love to drop OF Marty 
Cordova (.253, 10, 69) or Rick Aguilera (38 saves) in an effort to 
reduce their payroll to $10 million. 
</P>
<P>
	If not, GM Terry Ryan could be forced to part with ace Brad  
Radke (12-14, 4.30), the Twins' most marketable commodity. 
</P>
<P>
	Manager Tom Kelly doesn't even have the rich farm system that  
small-market partner Felipe Alou has in Montreal to cheer him up. 
</P>
<P>
                               *WEST    	
</P>
<P>
                          *Anaheim Angels    	
</P>
<P>
	Vaughn was signed as much to add fire to the clubhouse as he was  
to add a big bat to the lineup. 
</P>
<P>
	The Angels would like to deal outfielders Anderson (.294, 15,  
79) or Edmonds (.307, 25, 91) for pitching help, possibly Hentgen. 
Otherwise, manager Terry Collins has some difficult decisions to 
make with four outfielders -- the other two are RF Tim Salmon (.300, 
26, 88) and Darin Erstad (.296, 19, 82) -- for three spots. 
</P>
<P>
	The loss of SS Gary DiSarcina (.287, 3, 56) for three months  
with a broken arm puts a lot of pressure on newly-signed Andy 
Sheets (.242, 7, 29). 
</P>
<P>
	Ace Chuck Finley (11-9, 3.39) also has been slowed by an arm  
injury. He leads a pitching staff that has several question marks 
with Ken Hill (9-6, 4.98), recovering from elbow surgery, and 
37-year-old Tim Belcher (14-14, 4.27), who's trying to hang on. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
                           *Texas Rangers    	
</P>
<P>
	Texas didn't get the ace pitcher it needed, losing out in the  
Randy Johnson and Clemens sweepstakes. They did sign hard-working 
Mark Clark (9-14, 4.84) to replace Todd Stottlemyre, a midseason 
acquisition last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Free agent signee Palmeiro (.296, 43, 121) could miss the first  
few weeks with an injured knee, but he should flourish with the 
short right-field porch in Arlington. 
</P>
<P>
	Add RF Juan Gonzalez (.318, 45, 157), LF Rusty Greer (.306, 16,  
108) and C Ivan Rodriguez (.321, 21, 91), and the Rangers have one 
of the strongest lineups in the league. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
                         *Seattle Mariners    	
</P>
<P>
	How can a team with two of the best all-around players in the  
game -- Griffey (.284, 56, 146) and Rodriguez (.310, 42, 124, 46 
SBs) -- be so bad. Easy, no pitching. 
</P>
<P>
	The reasons for the lack of pitching stems from ownership's  
unwillingness to open its wallet and bungled moves by GM Woody 
Woodward. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Fassero (13-12, 3.97) and Jamie Moyer (15-9, 3.53) are  
capable starters, but the Mariners need either an ace -- like 
departed Randy Johnson -- or a strong bullpen to succeed as they 
move into the new Safeco Field July 15. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, they lost Mike Timlin, the most reliable member of  
baseball's most combustible bullpen. They replaced him with Jose 
Mesa (4.57, 1 save), who walked in the winning run twice in one 
week last year. That should do wonders for manager Lou Piniella's 
infamous temper. 
</P>
<P>
	Another season like last year's 76-85 mark could be enough to  
drive away Rodriguez and Griffey, who become free agents after the 
2000 season. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
                         *Oakland Athletics    	
</P>
<P>
	The A's are well short of competing, but at least they are  
moving in the right direction. Seven of their opening-day starters 
could be home grown and 3B Eric Chavez is the early favorite for 
rookie of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Along with last year's winner Ben Grieve (.288, 18, 89) and 1B  
Jason Giambi (.295, 27, 110), manager Art Howe has a core from 
which to build. SS Miguel Tejada (.233, 11, 45) is only 22 and 
already has shown improvement at the plate in spring training. 
</P>
<P>
	Rogers (16-8, 3.17) probably won't last the year in Oakland, but  
future ace Mark Mulder, the A's first-round pick in 1998, probably 
will end the season in the majors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990403.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 06:12:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Maine, N.H. Vie For Hockey Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- The coach looks at Jason Krog and sees  
Larry Bird. 
</P>
<P>
	Krog was very deserving of college hockey's top honor, the coach  
said, comparing the New Hampshire center's ability to control a 
game with that of basketball great Bird. 
</P>
<P>
	And that praise came from the coach of the rival team, Maine's  
Shawn Walsh. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's just an excellent player,'' Walsh said Friday after Krog  
received the Hobey Baker Award, the first time a New Hampshire 
player has been so honored. 
</P>
<P>
	One of Walsh's players, Steve Kariya, was among the 10 finalists  
for the award. 
</P>
<P>
	Krog and Kariya, both seniors, will play their college finale  
this evening as Hockey East rivals New Hampshire and Maine meet for 
the fifth time this season, with the NCAA championship on the line. 
</P>
<P>
	The schools split their four earlier meetings, although New  
Hampshire won the last two by one-sided scores, 6-1 and 4-1. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're disappointed with the way the regular season wound up.  
We didn't play well, and give them credit, they've played 
excellent,'' Kariya said. ``We'll need a better performance against 
them if we're going to get the job done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Walsh said it's no surprise the teams are very familiar with  
each other. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's exciting to be playing against our neighbor and traveling  
partner,'' he said. ``We've been on the road together, seen these 
guys so much on the ice, in hallways and hotel lobbies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New Hampshire coach Richard Umile added, ``This is obviously the  
rubber match. These are two teams that know each other real well 
and have a lot of respect for each other.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Walsh echoed that high regard, saying, ``It's turned into a nice  
rivalry instead of a bitter rivalry. The bottom line, though, is 
we're both going for the same prize and only one of us is going to 
get it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The appearance in the title game will be the first for New  
Hampshire, a 4-0 loser to Michigan in last year's semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the most satisfying things is that our team was picked  
to finish in the middle of our league. The guys really stepped it 
up and had career seasons,'' said Krog, who led the nation with 84 
points on 34 goals and 50 assists. 
</P>
<P>
	New Hampshire finished first in Hockey East by beating Maine  
twice and dropping the Black Bears to second, three points back. 
</P>
<P>
	Kariya, whose brother Paul plays on the same Arrowhead Pond ice  
with the Mighty Ducks of Anaheim, has 65 points this season, with 
27 goals. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wildcats (31-6-3) overpowered Michigan State 5-3 in the  
semis on Thursday, with Krog contributing two goals and an assist. 
</P>
<P>
	Maine (30-6-4) edged Boston College 2-1 in a semifinal match of  
Hockey East teams, with freshman Niko Dimitrakos tying the game in 
the third period, then setting up teammate Bobby Stewart for the 
winner in overtime. 
</P>
<P>
	Before Maine was banned from the tournament for three years for  
violating NCAA rules, the Black Bears won the 1993 national 
championship and lost in the title game to Boston University in 
1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
