<DOCNO> APW19990403.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 16:51:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> General Challenge Wins for Baffert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARCADIA, Calif. (AP) -- Trainer Bob Baffert won the Santa Anita  
Derby for the second straight year on Saturday with General 
Challenge. 
</P>
<P>
	The bad news for rival trainers is that Baffert also finished  
second with Prime Timber, a colt who almost didn't start because of 
a problem with his left hind foot. 
</P>
<P>
	After Baffert's second straight 1-2 finish in the race, he was  
asked what was the secret. 
</P>
<P>
	``Good horses,'' he said. ``You've got to have good horses.''  
</P>
<P>
	Baffert now has three wins and three seconds in four Santa Anita  
derbies, and it was two of the second-place finishers, Silver Charm 
and Real Quiet, who won the Kentucky Derby for him the last two 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	His previous Santa Anita Derby winners were Cavonnier, second in  
the Kentucky Derby in 1996, and Indian Charlie, third last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Prime Timber went off as the slight favorite, 2.40-1.  
</P>
<P>
	Desert Hero, the 2.50-1 second choice who had won his only two  
previous starts, finished third in the eight-horse field as the 
2.50-1 second betting choice. Prime Timber was the favorite at 
2.40-1. 
</P>
<P>
	The filly Honest Lady finished seventh and won't be going to  
Churchill Downs. 
</P>
<P>
	``All this race tells you is that you get to graduate,'' Baffert  
said. ``Now we get to go to the big show. This is where you start 
thinking Derby dreams.'' 
</P>
<P>
	General Challenge, a California-bred gelding, and Prime Timber,  
a Florida-bred colt, certainly have the ability to again make 
Baffert the star of the big show on May 1 at Churchill Downs by 
giving him an unprecedented third straight Kentucky Derby victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert will also have two top 3-year-old fillies -- Excellent  
Meeting, who won the Fantasy at Oaklawn Park on Friday, and 
Silverbulletday, who won the Ashland at Keeneland on Saturday -- in 
Kentucky. For now they are being pointed at the Kentucky Oaks on 
Derby Eve, and not the Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	General Challenge, wearing blinkers for the first time, took the  
lead just at the half-mile pole, opened up daylight and won by 3 1/2 
lengths over Prime Timber, who had been fifth with a half-mile 
remaining in the 1 1/8-mile race. Desert Hero finished another 3 1/2 
lengths back and 1 1/4 lengths in front of Charismatic, a 40-1 shot 
trained by D. Wayne Lukas. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were asking a lot of him today, just coming right back from  
Louisiana,'' jockey Gary Stevens said of General Challenge, who was 
fifth in the Louisiana Derby on March 14 for his only loss in five 
career starts. 
</P>
<P>
	``The addition of the blinkers was a big turnaround,'' Stevens  
said. ``It made him focus a lot more. He's got a lot of energy that 
can be used for a negative or a positive and it was a positive 
today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert said Prime Timber must have stepped on something on the  
track on Friday and bruised his left hind foot. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't think he was going to run today,'' Baffert said. The  
injury was soaked and treated overnight and, said Baffert, ``this 
morning he was fine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prime Timber now has three seconds and three victories in six  
career starts. 
</P>
<P>
	General Challenge, owned by John and Betty Mabee, was timed in  
1:48.92 under scale weight of 120 pounds and paid $7.60, $3.30 and 
$2.80 while earning $450,000 from the $750,000 purse. 
</P>
<P>
	Prime Timber, ridden by David Flores and owned by Aaron and  
Marie Jones, returned $3.40 and $2.40. Desert Hero, ridden by Corey 
Nakatani, paid $2.60. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if Desert Hero, who didn't race as a 2-year-old, would go  
to the Derby, trainer Richard Mandella said: ``No idea yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After Charismatic in fourth, the rest of the field in order was  
Walk That Walk, Capsized, Honest Lady and High Wire Act. 
</P>
<P>
	Honest Lady carried 115 pounds.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
